<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patriotic Overseas Chinese's Last Wish Fulfilled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Jimei University in east
China's port city of Xiamen has witnessed steady growth over the
past three years, according to the university's board of trustees
which met today.
</P>
<P>
The university was established in October 1994 at the last
request of Chen Jiageng, a patriotic overseas Chinese, who passed
away in 1961.
</P>
<P>
During his lifetime, he made donations to start educational
undertakings including kindergartens and vocational schools in his
hometown and Xiamen University, and financed 70 other primary and
middle schools in Fujian, in an effort to train more useful people
for the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, local governments have earmarked 102
million yuan (about 12.8 million US dollars) to the university for
its development. In addition, the city government has offered more
than 50 million yuan in subsidies to the school staff and students.
</P>
<P>
The school, with 68 majors in liberal arts, science and
engineering, has more than 7,300 students and over 2,300 employees.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that a new campus with a planned area of 600,000
sq.m. is under construction, and a computer center and a language
center are already in operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
