<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Sunday
rejected the call for a unilateral pullout from South Lebanon,
where 13 Israeli soldiers were killed in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the statement at the weekly Cabinet meeting
attended by senior defense officials to discuss the situation in
South Lebanon, especially the Friday incident that killed 12
Israeli soldiers and stunned the army as well as the whole
nation. (Israel-Netanyahu-Lebanese Pullout)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The leaders of Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Sunday called on Washington to double its
efforts to salvage the jeopardized peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Jordan's King Hussein and PNA
President Yasser Arafat made the call in a released statement at
the end of their two-and-half-hour urgent meeting convened to
coordinate their stance before the first trip to the Middle East
by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright this
week. (Egypt-Tripartite Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto returned
home Sunday after a four-day visit to China, part of events
marking the 25th anniversary of the normalization of Sino-Japanese
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Hashimoto held talks in Beijing with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng on a wide range of
issues. (Japan-Hashimoto-Return)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos said Sunday that
what he meant by keeping his options open includes endorsing his
successor from the ruling party for next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos caused public anxieties when he announced last week that
he was keeping his options open -- a remark interpreted by many as
a statement that Ramos was planning for re-election if amendments
are made to the Constitution. (Philippines-Ramos-Successor)
</P>
</TEXT>
