<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Gets 551 Million Dollars in Aid in 9 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Nepal received about 31.4
billion rupees (about 551 million U.S. dollars) in foreign aid
during the first nine months of the last fiscal year which ended
on July 14, a government report said.
</P>
<P>
About 98.2 percent of the aid came from the Nepal Aid Group,
which includes Japan, the United States, Australia, Canada,
Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Britain, Switzerland, the
Netherlands, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, grants and loans accounted for 22.5 percent and
77.5 percent respectively, said the Economic Survey for Fiscal
Year 1996-97 issued by the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
In the last fiscal year, Nepal received from the ADB and Japan
loans worth about 17.89 billion rupees (316 million dollars) for
its largest hydropower project "Kaligandaki A."
</P>
<P>
Assistance from the Nepal Aid Group constituted 83 percent and
82.6 percent respectively in fiscal years 1994-95 and 1995-96.
</P>
</TEXT>
