<HEADLINE> Simitis: Change of Status Quo in Cyprus Means War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today warned Turkey that any change of the existing status
quo in Cyprus by Ankara would mean war for Athens.
</P>
<P>
"Greece will go to war if Turkey attempts to overturn the
existing status quo in Cyprus," Simitis sounded the warning at a
press conference following the opening of the annual Thessaloniki
international trade fair in northern Greece today.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Greece backed the deployment of Russian-made
S-300 surface-to-air missiles in Cyprus because the island had the
right to enhance its defense capability.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that Athens supported a proposal by Cypriot
President Glafkos Clerides calling for the island's
demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a
breakaway state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which
has only been recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to unite with northern Cyprus if the
Cyprus government begins membership talks with the European Union
(EU). The EU has invited Cyprus to begin accession talks early
next year.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Turkey and northern Cyprus has signed a partial
integration pact which has already resulted in strong criticizism
from Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
