<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister on Tourism Campaign Trip to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Minister for Tourism
and Wildlife Protas Momanyi is now on a tourism campaign trip to
the United Kingdom to reassure British tourists that Kenya is a
safe destination for holiday makers, the Kenya News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The minister who left here on Saturday with a high-level
delegation, is scheduled to meet officials of British travel
agencies to brief them on the security situation in the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
Momanyi will also attend the 67th World Congress of the
American Society for Travel Agents scheduled to start on Monday
in Glasgow, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The minister's promotion campaign in Britain is reportedly
aimed at preventing further decline in tourist arrivals following
the recent violence in Kenya's Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 45 Kenyans have been killed in the continuous
violence in the port city of Mombasa and its environs since
August 13 when unidentified armed gangsters attacked police
stations at Likoni area.
</P>
<P>
The violence has dealt a serious blow to the country's tourism
industry, which is the biggest foreign exchange earner for Kenya.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least 5,000 tourists arrive in Mombasa
weekly during this season, but now the number has fallen
drastically by 30 to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
More than 15 charter flights land at the Moi International
Airport in Mombasa every week. But many of the fully booked
flights have been cancelled after the Likoni violence.
</P>
<P>
Kenya received 770,000 tourists last year and the tourism
industry earned the country 480 U.S. Dollars in foreign exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
