<HEADLINE> Tanzania's First Lady Stresses Women's Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's first lady
Anna Mkapa today stressed the importance of women's education in
the country, which she said is the pivot of economic development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a school fund-raising function in Arusha, northern
Tanzania, Mkapa underscored the urge for women's education to be
undertaken seriously at all levels as the only means to improve
the well-being of women in the country.
</P>
<P>
Parents have shown very little concern on the importance of
women's education, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The country's 1994 statistics showed that only 45.8 percent of
girl students in primary schools were selected for secondary
schools.
</P>
<P>
More specifically, Mkapa said, 43.4 percent of girls joined
form one of primary education in 1994. Only 31.6 percent of them
reached form four and 27.1 percent of the number completed form
six.
</P>
<P>
As for girl students in universities, the first lady said,
they accounted for an average of 19 percent of the total and
those who joined technical colleges took up 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Women's education is neglected not only in Tanzania, but in
the whole Africa, Mkapa added.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstance, Mkapa urged the government, the
international organizations and local community to relate the
well-being of women with education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
