<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Launches Air Raid in Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force known as ECOMOG today launched air raid at the port of
Freetown in an exercise to enforce embargo on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG aircraft this afternoon dropped two bombs, one of which
exploded and destroyed 10 vessels at the port, according to the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
No casualty figures are available at press time.
</P>
<P>
The air raid was targeted at unidentified vessels carrying
foodstuffs to Sierra Leone, which was under an economic embargo
imposed by west African countries.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG issued a statement on Friday, warning all ships and
aircraft to keep off the territorial waters and airspace of
Sierra Leone, where soldiers overthrew the legitimate government
in a coup in May.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG statement threatened to take military actions
against violators of the embargo, which was approved by the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) at its 20th
summit last weekend.
</P>
<P>
However, the military junta in Freetown refused the ECOWAS
decision, asserting that Sierra Leone is a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
A junta spokesman strongly condemned ECOMOG's air raid and
said the military regime had vowed to reinforce security at the
port.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's militia group known as Kamajors today
also launched an unsuccessful attack on the government soldiers
on a highway in southeast Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
A leader of the Kamajors, composed of traditional hunters,
said the attack was aimed to clear the area so that refugees from
neighboring Liberia who fled their country during the seven-year
civil war could easily go home.  
</P>
</TEXT>
