<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes EU Ambassadors Back to Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi tonight issued a positive signal to the European
countries, saying that EU ambassadors are welcome back to
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted the foreign minister as
saying that "EU ambassadors could return to Tehran any time at
their pleasure."
</P>
<P>
However, he did not mention any pre-conditions for the return
of the EU ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
Iran had insisted earlier that German ambassador should
return to his post at the tail of any return by EU envoys to
Iran -- a condition Germany views as an unacceptable "divide and
conquer" tactic.
</P>
<P>
But, Kharrazi warned that "European governments would do
better not to opt for unconventional decisions in their dealings
with Iran."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said during a brief visit to Tehran by EU envoy
Paul Meurtz Friday and Saturday, he had informed him of the
position of Iran on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy held two rounds of talks with Iranian Foreign
Ministry's Director General for Western Europe Ali Ahani in a
bid to solve the four-month diplomatic crisis between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that EU governments are now studying their
response. "Iran expected some change and revision in the
attitude of the EU toward Iran," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Kharrazi did not elaborate what the new stance Iran
has adopted toward the EU.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of Greece, all the EU countries recalled
their ambassadors home from Tehran after the Berlin Court last
April implicated top Iranian leaders in the killing of three
Kurdish dissidents and their translator in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
As a measure to punish Iran, EU also decided not to hold
bilateral ministerial-level meetings between Iran and any EU
member state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
