<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-07 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes Albright Resuscitates Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today expressed the hope that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's visit to the region would help reactivate the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Seating the Palestinians and Israelis on the negotiating table
is the required action," he told the press at the airport after
the departure of King Hussein of Jordan and Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat who joined President Hosni
Mubarak for a tripartite summit here today.
</P>
<P>
The only solution is that Palestinians and Israelis sit
together, negotiate and implement all the signed agreements, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Mubarak will contact with Arab leaders within the
coming days to brief them over the outcome of today's tripartite
summit.
</P>
<P>
Today's urgent summit was called to coordinate Arab stance
before Albright's first trip as the Secretary of State to the
region this week in the wake of Thursday's triple suicide bombing
in Jerusalem and the reimposition of tight Israeli closure on
Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released at the end of their two-and-half-hour
meeting, the three Arab leaders called on Washington to double its
efforts to salvage the jeopardized peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that a unified Arab position has actually existed
on the basis the Olso agreements.
</P>
<P>
Moussa blamed the Israeli policy for the recent wave of
terrorist attacks and called on the Israeli government to
re-assess its policies that "have given birth to many acts of
violence."
</P>
<P>
"The peace process did not deteriorate a few days or weeks
ago, but that its collapse was born to an Israeli policy that has
shattered the trust of Palestinian people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority and its people cannot be
held responsible for the current situation, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
"Neither the PNA nor Arafat has given the green light to any
acts of violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's threats not to
implement the troop redeployment in occupied territories or to
attack the Palestinian self rule areas, Moussa said that such
warnings have a negative impact of no benefit.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to revive the Palestinian-Israeli
peacemaking that has been in crisis since March over Jewish
settlement construction on the land the Palestinians want as part
of a future state.
</P>
<P>
The stalemate has been deepened by the suicide attacks in
Jerusalem, first on July 30 when two human bombs killed 15
Israelis and now on last Thursday when seven were killed by a
triple bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
Israel has held the PNA "indirectly responsible" for the
attacks and reimposed a complete closure on the West Bank and Gaza
Strip which had been eased earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
After the bombing, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu ruled out
handing over more land to Palestinians Friday until Arafat cracked
down on Muslim militants, accusing him of failing to honor a
commitment under interim peace accords to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel has redeployed its troops, handing over much of the Gaza
Strip and parts of the West Bank to Palestinian self-rule under
peace deals with Arafat starting in 1993. It is supposed to
withdraw from more of the West Bank in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
In today's press statement, the three leaders condemn terrorism
and the use of violence targeting innocent civilians and said that
violence runs contrary to the spirit of peace.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only two Arab countries that have
diplomatic ties with Israel and played important roles in peace
mediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
