<HEADLINE> Iranian President: Dialog Is Key to Kashmir Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today expressed the hope that the disputes on the issue of
Kashmir can be solved through negotiations between India and
Pakistan, Iranian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Khatami made the remark while meeting with the visiting Indian
Minister of State for External Affairs Saleem Iqbal Shervani who
arrived here Friday for a visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Shervani delivered a message of the Indian
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral to Khatami and briefed him on
progress in talks between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said both the Indian and Pakistan leaders are determined to
solve their disputes peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Kashmir, with an area of 220,000 square kilometers, locates in
the northern part of the Indian sub-continent. Both India and
Pakistan claim sovereignty over the area. The two countries have
fought three wars over the land and India is controlling two-thirds
of the area and Pakistan the rest.
</P>
<P>
Lauding the role of Iran and India in the regional cooperation
and in helping the Central Asian republics, Khatami said that
continued cooperation between the two countries will serve to cut
off the hands of aliens from that region and guarantee those
republics' independence.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed satisfaction with growing ties between Tehran
and New Delhi, saying "since we consider tranquility and peace to
be in the interests of regional states, we are ready to do all
within our power to improve relations among regional countries."
</P>
<P>
On bilateral ties, Shervani said that India is ready to
further expand its cooperation with Iran in economic, political
and cultural fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
