<HEADLINE> OIC Chief Starts Asian Tour on Islamic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) Ezz Eddine Al-Iraki
headed to Iran today on an Asian tour on a number of issues,
including the scheduled OIC conference and the Afghanistan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) quoted a statement released by the
Jeddah-based organization's General Secretariat as saying that the
tour would also include Pakistan and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Tehran, due to last until Wednesday,
Al-Iraki will discuss with Iranian official preparations for the
eighth conference of the OIC to be held in Tehran on December 10.
</P>
<P>
The KUNA report said he will also hold official talks on
Islamic issues and ways of resolving the current Afghanistan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, Al-Iraki held talks with Afghanistan Taliban
Prime Minister Lakhdar Ibrahimi who is on a visit to Saudi Arabia
on efforts to stop the civil war in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources were quoted as saying that Al-Iraki and
Ibrahimi expressed their belief that it was about time to stop the
civil war in the war-torn Asian country.
</P>
<P>
It was disclosed that the Taliban movement expressed readiness
to hold dialog with the Afghan rivals to put an end to the blood
shedding.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban army overran the capital of Kabul a year ago and
now controls the southern two-thirds of the country.
</P>
<P>
Al-Iraki will pay a visit to Bangladesh from September 12 to
18.
</P>
<P>
OIC was established in 1970 and groups 46 Islamic countries.
</P>
