<HEADLINE> Angolan Minister Arrives for SADC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, September 7 (Xinhua )-- Angolan Minister of
Construction P. de Castro Vandunen arrived here today on behalf
of President Eduardo Dos Santos to attend the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) summit to be held Monday, a liaison
officer with the summit said here today.
</P>
<P>
The sudden change of Angolan leader for the SADC summit was
made this morning, said SADC liaison officer Diana Nkhulembe,
adding that the reason for the change was not available.
</P>
<P>
Angola, which has been devastated by more than two decades of
civil war, is said to have been urging for the southern African
group's help in bringing final peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
"SADC is interested in bringing a final peace into Angola,"
said Alfred Nzo, Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the
sub-regional group.
</P>
<P>
The SADC countries, all members of the United Nations, have
been helping Angola for a final peace through their strict
observance of the United Nations resolutions over the peace
process in the country, Nzo said today.
</P>
<P>
The group members have observe the UN sanctions in late August
to prevent the entry into or transit through their territories of
all senior officials of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA ) and of adult members of their
immediate families, he said.
</P>
<P>
They have been required by the UN resolution to close
immediately and completely all UNITA offices in their countries.
</P>
<P>
SADC members also express their readiness to consider the
imposition of additional measures with UN, such as trade and
financial restrictions, if UNITA does not fully comply with its
obligations under the Lusaka Peace Accord signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
SADC has been urging for direct talks between Angolan
President Dos Santos and Jonas Savimbi, chairman of the former
rebel movement UNITA, which will contribute to the reduction of
tensions and national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The immediate challenge facing SADC is to maintain democracy,
peace and security, so as to create an atmosphere of confidence
and trust in and among the member states, said Nelson Mandela,
SADC chairman and South African President.
</P>
<P>
SADC has established an organ on politics, defense and
security, a mechanism for peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Regional integration will dominated Monday's summit here.
</P>
</TEXT>
