<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel's New Chips to Reach Retail Customers First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Intel Corporation, the
world's largest chip producer, will ship its newest generation of
microprocessor chips today to retail customers first.
</P>
<P>
Chain stores like CompUSA, instead of corporations like
Hewlett-Packard, will become the first to see the new chips,
according to a report by the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
The new chip, the latest in the Pentium line, contains the
smallest transistors Intel has ever made for commercial sale. As a
result, it packs more of these transistors -- the switches that
control the flow of electrical impulses in the circuitry -- into a
smaller space than ever before.
</P>
<P>
The new technology provides computer users with twin benefits:
Their machines can perform more functions faster while using up to
50 percent less power. This makes the new chips especially useful
in small, battery-powered portable computers -- the
fastest-growing segment of the computer industry, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The new processors, operating at 200 and 233 megahertz with the
company's MMX multimedia technology, are the first products made
using Intel's most advanced manufacturing technology. The circuit
lines on the chip are 0.25 microns wide; more than 300 of them set
side by side would barely equal the width of a human hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Beats U.S. 3-0 in Under-17 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Jorge Castro scored in
the 66th minute to help beat the United States 3-0 in a second
round match Monday at the Under-17 World Cup soccer tournament in
Alexandria, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In the first round, Brazil defeated Austria 7-0 and the United
States was trounced 4-0 by Oman in Group C.
</P>
<P>
In the 21st minute of the second half, Castro powered through the
U.S. defense to drill the ball home in the lower left hand corner of
the net.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen minutes later, Adiel Amorim scored again with another
well placed shot to the left.
</P>
<P>
The team's third goal was scored by Matuzalem Silva who nailed a
shot deflected by the U.S. defense and sent it ricocheting from the
left post across the goal line and into the right side of the net.
</P>
<P>
Brazil will play Oman on Thursday, while the U.S. meets Austria
on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
