<HEADLINE> Swedish Social Democratic Party Congress Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The 33rd congress of the
ruling Swedish Social Democratic Party opened today in Sweden'
northern city of Sundsvall.
</P>
<P>
On the congress's agenda are tax policy, the outlines of which
were approved by the party at a meeting on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the congress vowed to fight for welfare with
priority going to health care, care of the elderly, the
handicapped and schools.
</P>
<P>
They argued that the special tax on high-income earners should
be retained till 1999 when it will be imposed merely on the top
layer of high-income earners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the party has set a long-term target that less than
15 percent of income earners in the country, compared with the
current 19 percent, will be required to pay state tax.
</P>
<P>
The congress, which will conclude on September 14, will also
discuss the development of democracy and environmental
protection. 
</P>
