<HEADLINE> Mayor From Far-Right French Party Given Jail Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A French court suspended a
three-month jail sentence and levied a 50,000-franc (about 8,300
U.S. dollars) fine in a verdict against Catherine Megret, the
mayor of the southwestern city of Vitrolles.
</P>
<P>
Megret was elected from the far-right National Front (FN) party
led by Jean-Marie Le Pen early this year.
</P>
<P>
The Correctional Tribunal of Aix-en-Provence condemned Megret
for making racist statements taunting immigrants and suggesting
racial inequality in a February interview with the German daily
Berliner Zeitung (Berlin Daily).
</P>
<P>
Statements of this kind violate French law.
</P>
<P>
Catherine Megret, who is the wife of FN's number two figure
Brono Megret, said in the interview that there were differences
between races and between genes. She also said that immigrants in
France want nothing but money. 
</P>
