<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Militiamen Clash over Narcotic Leaves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Three people were killed
and four others were wounded when armed militiamen among the
supporters of Hussein Mohamed Aidid exchanged heavy fire at Afgoe
road near the Somali capital Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said, the shooting began when a convoy of
vehicles transporting khat were refused access to reach the
capital Mogadishu by militiamen at a check point near the
strategic K-7 junction.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness told the reporters that two people died on the
spot when the militiamen at the check point managed to snatch the
khat cargo off one of the trucks transporting the narcotic
leaves. The check point was immediately deserted after the
militiamen ran away with their booty.
</P>
<P>
Annoyed by the fatalities and material loss, the militiamen
escorting the drug khat angrily attacked two other vehicles
suspected to have belonged to the same clan of the robbers,
killing a man and wounding three others at the former maintenance
factory on the industrial street in South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Despite the incident, the road remains open for the traffic
today following the intervention of local elders who succeeded in
dismantling the newly erected check point. The elders also
discussed ways to prevent the repetition of such incidents.
</P>
<P>
This is the third attack against the khat convoys in the same
area between the former maintenance factory and the K-7 junction
within two weeks. The khat fighting has claimed the lives of more
than eight militiamen in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
In another development, North Mogadishu faction leader Ali
Mahdi Mohamed, hosted in North Mogadishu today a rally attended
by politicians and traditional leaders returned from a meeting in
South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the headquarters of Ali Mahdi said, the
politicians and elders led by Abdulqasim Salad Hassan, former
interior minister of late Siad Barre's government, and Intellect
Ahmed Rage, former mayor of Mogadishu, discussed ways of
restoring confidence among the Somali people so as to pave the
way for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation met last week with South Mogadishu faction
leader Hussein Aidid and some of his senior officials as well as
representatives of Osman Hassan Ali Atto near Bosnia, Somalia,
for similar purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
