<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders Sign Declaration for Gender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Equality
</P>
<P>
BLANTYRE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) today pledged to spearhead a
inequalities" in the region.
</P>
<P>
The pledge is contained in SADC's "Declaration on Gender and
Development" signed by the twelve leaders of the member states in
the Blantyre summit this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A book entitled "Into the Future: SADC and Gender", was
launched here at the SADC summit, whose documents recommendations
were made at a strategy workshop in January#and endorsed by the
SADC Council of Ministers in Windhoek, Namibia in February, on
integrating gender considerations into the work of the
sub-regional group.
</P>
<P>
In a foreword to the book, South African President Nelson
Mandela, Chairman of SADC, declares that "As leaders of SADC, we
recognize that freedom cannot be achieved unless women attain
equality, respect and dignity through their full participation in
every respect of our regional endeavor."
</P>
<P>
Gertrude Mongella, chairperson of the U.N. Fourth World
Conference on Women, said today as an honored guest at the
summit, that SADC women and men who have fought side by side
against colonialism and apartheid, need to conquer the last
frontier of gender inequality in the region.
</P>
<P>
She said, to a round of warm applause, that women should be
taken as a force of peace on the continent, stressing that the
message from African women against war is: "Enough is enough."
</P>
<P>
While some SADC members have made progress toward gender
equality, disparity between men and women still exists in the
areas of legal rights, power sharing and decision making, access
to and control over productive resources, education and health,
said the book.
</P>
<P>
SADC is aiming at a goal of 30 percent of women in political
and decision making structure by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The book urged members of the sub-regional group to reform
all laws, amend constitutions and change social practices which
"still subject women to discrimination."
</P>
<P>
SADC is one of the few regional organizations in Africa and
the world which formally recognizes the importance of gender
equality to the achievement of its twin objectives of democracy
and development.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional group which aims at a fully developed common
market by the year 2000, have 12 members, namely Angola,
Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South
Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
