<HEADLINE> Talks Arranged for Taiwan Businessmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Organizing Committee of
the '97 China Investment and Trade Talks today held a symposium
for businessmen from Taiwan to discuss the expansion of
economic and trade relationship across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 Taiwan entrepreneurs, headed by Xu Shengfa,
Chairman of the Board of the Taiwan Industrial and Commercial
Federation, attended the meeting, which was jointly sponsored by
the federation and the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Li Bingcai, deputy director of the Taiwan Affairs Office of the
State Council, delivered a speech, saying "people on both sides of
the Taiwan Strait have the same origin. We take the firm position, as
always, that economic exchanges and cooperation should be
developed on the basis of equality and mutual benefit."
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, the mainland has taken a series of measures to
promote exchanges and cooperation across the strait. "Though being
blocked by some manmade obstacles, economic cooperation between
the island and mainland is still surging forward," Li noted.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of June, the total trade volume
across the strait had reached 105.3 billion US dollars, with more
than 30,000 Taiwan-funded enterprises founded on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation could be increased in the agriculturial and energy
sectors, as well as in reforms of the mainland's state-run
enterprises," said Li, adding that businessmen from Taiwan will
find more opportunities in the regions of central and west China.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the issue of Taiwan investors' rights and interests
on the mainland, he repeated, "their legal rights will surely be
protected by laws and regulations worked out by governments at all
levels over the past decades."
</P>
<P>
Li also talked about direct linkage across the strait. "It will
greatly benefit economic and trade development on both sides. We
shall, as always, work toward its realization,"
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were Sun Zhenyu, Deputy Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation and businessmen from 26
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
