<HEADLINE> Monitoring Committee Meets to Consider Lebanon's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The five-nation committee
monitoring the cease-fire in south Lebanon met today in Naqoura on
the Israeli-Lebanese border to consider complaints lodged by
Lebanon and Israel against each other following last Friday's
fierce battle.
</P>
<P>
It is the 25th such meeting since the committee was established
under the truce accord reached in April, 1996 to end a 16-day
Israeli blitz of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Lebanon lodged a complaint, accusing Israel of
launching a commando raid last Friday on Lebanon in which a
Lebanese woman was killed and six civilians wounded, Lebanese
radio Voice of People reported.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Israel condemned Lebanon in its complaint
that last Saturday Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
killed an Israeli army officer in its attack on an Israeli troops
position in south Lebanon, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
It would take several days before the representatives of the
monitoring committee coming from Lebanon, Syria, Israel, France
and the United States could point out who violated the truce
accord which prohibits attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Israeli soldiers were killed, four others wounded, and
one missing when Lebanese army and resistance fighters ambushed a
16-member Israeli commando Friday who landed on the village of
Nsariyyeh, about 45 kilometers north of the Israeli border in
attempt to explode a Shiite movement Amal base near the village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
