<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Calls for African Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim,
secretary-general of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
today called on African countries to give their first priority to
the continent's economic integration.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the summit of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) which opened here today, Salim said, "SADC is
one of the five pillars upon which our African economic community
stands. We are, therefore, gathered under one of the great
pillars for regional cooperation and integration in Africa."
</P>
<P>
He believed that through building capacities for regional and
continental economic integration, Africa will be able to reverse
the current trend of operating on the periphery, and thus moving
the continent to the center stage of the global economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief urged all African governments and people to
accord priority to the issues of economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
He also called for creating an environment to promote and
facilitate the participation of the private sector in economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
The African Economic Community shall be established mainly
through coordination, harmonization and the progressive
integration of the programs of the regional economic communities,
Salim said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the serious human and material constraints facing
all the African Regional Economic Communities (RECS), Salim
called for avoidance of duplication.
</P>
<P>
"Our prime objective should be to ensure that all RECS
programs are going in the same direction of facilitating eventual
continental integration," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim noted particularly that Africa's development efforts
have continued to be seriously undermined by the prevalence of
conflicts in some regions of the continent.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he accused the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) of not complying with the Lusaka
Peace Agreement signed in 1994, saying that it constitutes a
destabilizing force in that region of Angola.
</P>
<P>
"Conflicts are threatening to destroy the social fabric of our
society, with significant impact on the socio-economic
development of our countries and our region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief urged African countries to continue to
coordinate their efforts to address issues of peace, security,
and stability in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
