<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Environment Ministers Meet in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Environment ministers from
central and East European countries held an informal talk with
their counterparts from the European Union (EU) today to discuss
pre-accession preparation on environment issues.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on the implementation of EU environmental
legislation in the central and East European countries, which is a
part of an environmental approximation program.
</P>
<P>
The countries that apply for EU membership will have to adopt
environment protection measures with precise timetables and
establish a comprehensive mechanism for monitoring progress.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive legislative guide, the first of its kind ever
produced by the EU's executive body European Commission and
distributed among discussion participants, represents a
step-by-step road map to implementation.
</P>
<P>
EU Environment Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard described the
talk, the third since the inauguration of the program, as showing
"the way ahead on the road to membership for all 10 associated
countries."
</P>
<P>
Participants believe these informal consultations have proven
to be a very practical formula for constructive discussions
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission's Agenda 2000 suggests that such
informal talks should replace the existing structural dialogue as
the forum for general discussions on accession-related issues in
all policy areas.
</P>
<P>
The 10 applicant countries include Bulgaria, the Czech
Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Romania,
Slovakia and Slovenia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
