<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Marks International Day on Wiping out Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials today call
on their countrymen to do more to wipe out illiteracy and make a
significant contribution to the international learn-to-read
campaign.
</P>
<P>
"Wiping out illiteracy in a country with the largest population
in the world is of international significance," said Yu Zengfu,
secretary-general of the Chinese Committee of UNESCO, at a meeting
to mark the International Day on Wiping out Illiteracy, which is
today.
</P>
<P>
He said China's work has aroused international attention and
the country is actively cooperating with UNESCO in this field.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Tianbao, vice-minister of the State Education Commission,
said that some 24.4 million Chinese between the ages of 15 and 47
have learned to read and write over the past five years, bringing
the illiteracy rate down from 10.4 percent to 6.1 percent in this
age group.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the work has benefited China's economic
development and human rights course.
</P>
<P>
However, there is still a large illiterate population, most of
them are women living in the countryside, he added. Therefore,
governments at different levels must work still harder to bring
the illiteracy rate further down to two percent in the 15-47 age
group in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Kaixun, minister in charge of the State Education
Commission, presented awards to those people and units that have
made great contributions to the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
