<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurostat Publishes GDP Data of EU Applicant Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Slovenia is expected to
become the most promising candidate for membership in the European
Union (EU) as Eurostat published and released its gross domestic
product (GDP) data today.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat, EU's statistical arm, reported that according to
available data from 1995, the GDP of the former Yugoslav republic
accounts for 59 percent of the EU average, or almost 90 percent of
that in Greece which is a EU member state with the lowest GDP per
capita in purchasing power standards.
</P>
<P>
Combined GDP purchasing power per capita standards in 10
central and eastern European countries applying for EU membership
is 32 percent of the EU average, according to the latest report by
Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
The 10 countries are Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Romania, Slovakia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Total GDP of the 10 countries in purchasing power standards is
9.1 percent of the EU figure, while their annual GDP growth rate
plus that of Cyprus, which is also trying to join EU, stands at
5.2 percent, or more than twice EU's 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Poland accounts for 35 percent of the total GDP of the 10
applicant countries, while Romania leads in the annual GDP growth
rate with 7.1 percent, followed by Poland and Slovakia, both at
7.0 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabbah Seals Secret Mining Pact With Iran: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ousted civilian president
Tejan Kabbah signed a secret agreement with Iran for tapping
Sierra Leone's mineral and aquatic resources during his visit to
Teheran last September, Trade ministry officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary of State Alusent Bangura, in an interview
with Xinhua, said the agreement covered the rutile mines at
Mobimbi, the bauxite industry at Mokanji, both in the south and
Marampa mines at port Loko in the north.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, according to the official, was never ratified
by parliament as mandated by law in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"It was kept a secret between delegates who accompanied Kabbah
to Teheran, Dangura added.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources recalled that immediately after Kabbah
returned from Teheran, a 20-man Iranian government delegation
visited Sierra Leone and made an on-the-spot assessment of mining
areas in the country including the lucrative diamond industry in
the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
After the visit, Iran announced that the cost of
rehabilitation of the mining industry in Sierra Leone would be
between one to two million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
