<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Army Moves Into Port, Ready to Fight: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A heavily armed contingent
of the Sierra Leone army backed by anti-aircraft guns, moved into
the country's main port in the east of the capital today to ward
off any air attack on ships now berth in the harbor, a government
statement said.
</P>
<P>
We are prepared to defend the port and its vital installation
and if this means war with the Nigerians, so be it, declared
Gaptain Abubakarr Kamara who is coordinating the operation.
</P>
<P>
The build-up of security is a follow-up of a magnetic rocket
and cluster bombs attack by a Nigerian Air force jet on Saturday
and Sunday on a merchant ship berth at the ports discharging
19,000 tons of rice from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The attacks wounded three para-military personnel guarding the
ship, damaged the General Manager's Office and over 15 imported
cars from Belgium.
</P>
<P>
"I can say the damage caused can be put at over 3 million U.
S. Dollars," said General Manager, Captain Patrick Kemokai.
</P>
<P>
Residents near the ports said they saw the jet took off from
the Lungi International Airport, currently occupied by a
contingent or the Nigerian army and headed toward the direction
of the port, about five miles away.
</P>
<P>
"We heard deafening sounds as the bombs were dropped and then
the jet flew back to Lungi," one eye witness said.
</P>
<P>
State radio described the act as "a provocation and violation
of the call by West African leaders at their recent summit at
Abuja for a peaceful resolution of the political impasse in
Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
The ground Commander of Ecomog forces in Sierra Leone, colonel
Max Khobe told Xinhua in a telephone interview that they have "a
mandate from ECOWAS to enforce a blockade and sanctions against
Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats said they are worried over the increasing
tension building up between both sides which can trigger off a
large scale war if it is not checked.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has so far not okayed ECOWAS
decision to impose sanctions on Sierra Leone, observers here
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
