<HEADLINE> China Values Ties with Australia: Li Peng  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China values its relationship
with Australia, and advancement of bilateral ties in politics,
economy, science and technology is the common goal and in the best
interests of the two peoples, Premier Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting this afternoon with Australian Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of Trade Tim Fischer, Li extended a welcome
to Fischer who is visiting China for the second time since
assuming office.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the establishment of
diplomatic ties between China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
In the past 25 years, Li said, bilateral friendly relations of
cooperation have developed in a big way.
</P>
<P>
Fischer is leading a government and business delegation here
following Prime Minister John Howard's China visit at the end of
last March, he said, noting that this shows that Australia
attaches great importance to its relations with China.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, bilateral relations have experienced positive
changes, and more areas of common interest are appearing, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"Bilateral trade ties are being conducted on a long-term and
steady basis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries are important trade partners to each other
and the two-way investment is continuing to increase. The two
countries compensate for each other's economic deficiency and
there are broad prospects for cooperation of mutual interest," the
premier stressed.
</P>
<P>
Although the two countries have different social systems,
ideology and levels of development, they both belong to the Asia-
Pacific region, and are member states of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation and the Regional Forum of the Association of the
Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
