<HEADLINE> India Will Keep Nuclear Option Open: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 8 (Xinhua)-- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral said today that India would prefer its nuclear option
open to meet unforeseen circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the two-day international seminar on the role of
nuclear energy for sustainable development here, he said that
India has proved time and again that even when it has capability
to make nuclear weapons, it would not do so.
</P>
<P>
He said that use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes would
continue to be the government's policy. He urged scientists to
devise technologies that bring down the cost of production of
nuclear power to make it competitive with other technologies.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the International Atomic Energy
Agency (IAEA) would guide India in cheaper nuclear power
generation, safe disposal of nuclear wastes and plant safety
factors.
</P>
<P>
IAEA Chief Hans Blix today said that the Indian designed 500MW
reactor would be subjected to international peer review.  
</P>
