<HEADLINE> Diana's Bodyguard Still Unable to Speak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Trevor Rees-Jones, bodyguard of
Princess Diana and her friend Dodi Al Fayed, has regained
consciousness in a Paris hospital but is still unable to talk.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones was severely injured in the car crash that killed
Diana and Dodi.
</P>
<P>
The Public Assistance of Paris said today in a communique that
Rees-Jones will remain hospitalized under intensive care "for an
unknown period of time."
</P>
<P>
The bodyguard, staying at the Pitie-Salpetriere Hospital of
Paris, is suffering from pulmonary contusion.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today through the British embassy, the
family of Rees-Jones said he is recovering but cannot talk to
investigators about the fatal car crash.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones was the only survivor among the four persons who
were in the Mercedes 280 that crashed into a supporting pillar
after entering the Alma underground pass in downtown Paris.
</P>
<P>
His testimony will provide the final determining evidence
regarding the accident which is essential for the judge to decide
whether the 10 photographers, under investigation for pursuing
Diana at mid-night of August 30, are guilty.
</P>
<P>
contradictory statements have been issued by photographers, the
Al Fayed family, some witnesses and police about what actually
happened that night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
