<HEADLINE> S.Korean Provincial Governor Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Governor Rhee In-je of South
Korea's Kyonggi Province, who is very popular in polls, resigned
from his post today without mentioning whether or not he would
join the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to step down from my gubernatorial post," Rhee told
a news conference. He said the times and the people crave change.
</P>
<P>
Rhee did not elaborate on his future plans. He did say,
however, that he would try to blossom in "big politics" as he had
promised.
</P>
<P>
An aide to Rhee said he would decide on whether to run the
presidential election as an independent candidate after Chusok
(Mid-Autumn Festival) which falls on September 15.
</P>
<P>
Rhee, an aide to President Kim Young-sam, became governor of
the populous province encompassing Seoul in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by his popularity, Rhee is expected to eventually
join the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the race is a four-way competition between Lee
Hoi-chang from the ruling party, Kim Dae-jung, Kim Jong-pil and
Seoul Mayor Cho Soon from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Rhee's resignation came at a time when Lee Hoi-chang, who is in
third-place in the popularity polls, is under fire over his sons'
alleged evasion of military service.
</P>
<P>
Lee's opponents, which include some Rhee supporters, are
demanding his replacement in an apparent move to promote Rhee as
an alternative candidate.
</P>
<P>
But some critics and ruling party officials say it is far from
certain whether Rhee would be able to retain his popular public
image after joining the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that since only a few lawmakers among Lee's
opponents would support Rhee's presidential bid, Rhee is likely to
join hands with Lee in a party power-sharing deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
