<HEADLINE> Malawian Leader Hails Progress in Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President
Bakili Muluzi, host for the on-going Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Summit, today hailed the Angolan peace
negotiation as a "victory".
</P>
<P>
Opening the SADC summit here this morning, Muluzi said with
the assistance of the international community, the U.N. and SADC
leaders, Angola has succeeded in bringing Jonas Savimbi, leader
of the former rebel movement National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
"Sincere appreciation and gratitude" should be given to
Zambian President Fredrick Chiluba for the role he played in
leading the negotiation process, Muluzi said.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian head of state fully believed that members of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) could work together
toward unleashing the creative potential of the people in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The most significant factor for SADC is that apart from a few
isolated incidents, the region enjoys peace, he noted, adding
that peace, democracy and respect for human rights would continue
to deepen throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
Political reforms such as constitutional and electoral
systems, which ensure transparency and predictability of the
systems in the region are still continuing, according to Muluzi.
</P>
<P>
Without political stability, there can be no significant
social or economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has sent its Minister of Construction
P. De Castro Vandunen to attend the SADC summit, representing
President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
The sudden change of Angolan leader for the SADC summit was
made Sunday morning, said Diana Nkhulembe, SADC liaison officer
yesterday, adding that the reason for the change was not
available.
</P>
<P>
Angola, which has suffered a civil war for nearly two decades,
have been receiving help from the southern African group for a
final peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi said that SADC members need to redouble their efforts
to take full advantage of the resources and capitalize the trade
and investment opportunities in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian president also urged his countrymen and regional
neighbors to improve the productivity of their manufacturing
industries, without which no trade could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He also called on SADC members to tackle the issues of
education and training together to equip the region for the 21st
century and beyond. 
</P>
</TEXT>
