<HEADLINE> Algerian Army Put on Alert Against Islamic Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Algerian army has been put
on maximum alert by President Liamine Zeroual to "take exceptional
measures" against Islamic militants, the Arabic daily Al Hayat
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reported decision by Zeroual came after Islamic militants
massacred 300 villagers on August 28, and 80 others on September 5
near the capital city Algiers. The militants were also held
responsible for a bombing attack last week in Algiers that killed
at least three.
</P>
<P>
Al Hayat, which is sold in several European capitals, quoted an
unidentified high-ranking official in Algeria as saying that the
130,000-strong National People's Army (ANP) of Algeria is now on
maximum alert, and is on the front line of the war against the
insurgency by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
It said that some personalities "in and outside the power" are
beginning to exert pressure on Zeroual to take exceptional
measures, including extending the power of the army in fighting
Islamic militants and imposing a curfew in the "flash spot"
regions that are haunted by terror.
</P>
<P>
According to Agence France-Presse, civilians in some parts of
Algiers region are organizing armed self-defense militiamen to
patrol the outskirts of their residential areas.
</P>
<P>
The ANP is headed by General Mohamed Lamari, the number two of
the Algerian authority, who reportedly advocates a ruthless war on
Islamic militants and opposes any compromise.
</P>
<P>
Algerians have been living under a state of emergency since
1992, when Islamic militants staged an insurgency after the army
canceled an election victory by the outlawed Islamic Salvation
Front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
