<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development of Human Resources Urged in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Nelson Mandela, President of
South Africa, said here today that the development of human
resources is crucial to the final integration on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the SADC summit here this morning,
Mandela said, gender, productivity and respect for human rights
as well as the basic tenets of good governance, through which
human resources are expected to be fully tapped, are critical to
the socio-economic advancement of the people in te region.
</P>
<P>
The task of transforming SADC into a "dynamic development
community is urgent", Mandela, who doubles as Chairman of
Southern African Development Community (SADC), said.
</P>
<P>
SADC will give "unequivocal recognition that gender equality
is a fundamental human right to be realized through equatable
representation of women and men in decision-making structures as
well as equal access to resources, the chairman noted.
</P>
<P>
Remarkable progress has been made in engaging key
stake-holders such as private sector and civic associations in
the development of the sectoral protocols that will guide
regional integration, he said.
</P>
<P>
Productivity and competitiveness are regarded by the SADC
chairman as "indispensable weapons" in the war against poverty,
deprivation and marginalization.
</P>
<P>
Mandela urged the southern African organization to raise a
collective voice of concern where necessary.
</P>
<P>
The basis of good governance on the inter-state level of SADC,
Mandela said, is the basic principles of respecting for the
sovereignty of member states and non-interference in one
another's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called on all SADC member states to abide by the
principles, values and ideals, which have been the the foundation
for the making of the regional group.
</P>
<P>
The SADC head said that they are striving for the creation of
a society in which all stakeholders -- labor, business and other
elements of civil society - can play a meaningful role for the
betterment of all.
</P>
<P>
The right of citizens to participate unhindered in political
activities in their countries is a "non-negotiable basic
principle," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
The creation of structures within which public opinion can be
mobilized and given expression is an undeniable part of the
democratic process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela urged SADC members to free their people, especially
children, from the savage threat of millions of explosive weapons
recklessly scattered across the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
