<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facility Overinvestment Blamed for Industrial Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Overinvestment in facility
expansion by major South Korean industries, including automobiles,
shipbuilding, petrochemistry and semiconductors, have worsened the
profitability of domestic businesses, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
The excess capacity rate of the industries, which remains above
the 20-percent level, has seriously hurt profit, the Korea
Institute of Finance said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of current profits against industry's total facility
investments, a barometer of the profitability of industrial
output, stood at 6 percent in the 1990-1995 period, half of the 12
percent recorded by the Japanese industry during the same period,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The institute said profitability had worsened since last year
and would continue to decline, compared with big profits gained by
local semiconductor producers during the boom years of 1994 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
It said excessive investments by local companies in heavy and
chemical industries has resulted in a buildup of excess capacity
as well as a drop in profitability.
</P>
<P>
The institute warned that overcapacity would become even more
serious in the coming years, considering the number of massive
investment projects planned and those already underway, such as
Samsung Motors Inc.'s entry into the automobile industry.
</P>
<P>
"Companies need to focus on developing new technologies and
enhancing efficiency by specializing in specific sectors, rather
than diversifying into various lines, to help solve the
overcapacity problems," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also said "the government for its part should encourage
businesses toward this direction." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
