<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nigeria May Adopt Phased Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria may adopt a three-phased
privatization program, as it is the recommendation by the Vision 2010
Committee, the country's first and foremost long-term planning body.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Daily Champion newspaper, the privatization
program will run for over 12 years starting from next year.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase that ends at the year 2000, public enterprises
such as the National Electric Power Authority, Nigerian
Telecommunications, the downstream operations of the Nigerian National
Petroleum Corporation and urban water utilities will revert to private
ownership and control.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the committee want these firms privatized first because
of their size and their socio-economic impact as well as hopes of
spinning off immediate growth of the economy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The second phase will run from 2001 to 2005, during which
infrastructure and other public enterprises not operating efficiently
or had never commenced operations, but which require substantial
capital injection will be sold off.
</P>
<P>
The report gave the example the Ajaokuta Steel Complex, which has
cost the country five billion U.S. dollars since its construction was
started a decade ago but has never been finished.
</P>
<P>
Other enterprises that may be privatized in this phase include the
Nigerian Railway Corporation, the Nigerian Coal Corporation, the Delta
steel plant and others, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The final phase will see those public enterprises with little
impact on the economy, unfinished and abandoned projects and all
others not yet affected by the exercise, being privatized.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's privatization practice began in late 1980s under the
supervision of the defunct Technical Committee on Privatization and
Commercialization now known as the Bureau of Public Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In its final report released in 1993, the committee said
government, by that date, had partial or whole equity ownership of
about 574 enterprises, of which about 145 had been privatized or
commercialization.
</P>
<P>
The program was expected to have been restarted at the beginning of
this year, but the government later put it off, claiming that there
was a need to further study the issue.
</P>
<P>
As the Vision 2010 Committee is to submit its final report later
this month, the head of state, General Sani Abacha, may however be
sold the idea, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the committee and former head of the interim
government before Abacha, Chief E.A.O. Shonekan, in a recent interview
with Xinhua, stressed the need to encourage competition in the
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
