<HEADLINE> Former Chief of Staff Returns to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- General Issac Lumago, former
Chief of Staff of Uganda Army, has returned after his 20 years of
exile, ''the New Vision'' paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
A three-member team including Grace Nyakwenegura, a private
secretary of Uganda President Yoweri Museveni, arranged the
general's return. They travelled to Kinshasa to pick up the
general and accompanied him in flying back last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lumago lived in Kinshasa for the last 18 years and did his
business there, leaving his family in Koboko in the northwest.
Kamanda Bataringaya, the Ugandan Ambassador in Congo or ex Zaire,
was also on the flight.
</P>
<P>
Lumago was one of about a thousand former officers fled the
country when former Uganda dictator Idi Amin was overthrown in
1979. But he did not involve in any activity of rebel groups
against President Yoweri Museveni, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni is expected to meet the general, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Lumago is a 58-year-old ballistic expert trained in former
Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
The former general returned to his home in the northwest which
are still haunted by the rebels of Uganda National Rescue Front,
part two (UNRF ii). Some 130 rebels of UNRF ii rebels have been
charged with treason recently. This rebel group recruited a
hundred of youths for military training to fill their ranks, a
recent report said. 
</P>
