<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Delegation Visits Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government's
International Cooperation Agency has announced plans
to cooperate with Chinese experts from Yunnan Province in
preparing a feasibility study for the construction of a new
hydropower station on the Jinsha River.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from the agency recently visited the proposed site
for the Jin'anqiao Hydropower Station on the Jinsha River in the
upper reaches of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Niu Shaoyao, deputy governor of Yunnan
Province, the head of the Japanese delegation expressed hope that
the cooperation agreement will be finalized in the near future. He
noted that the agency will provide technical support and join in
research related to the project.
</P>
<P>
The Jinsha River meanders some 3,496 km through Yunnan and is
the longest river in the province in southwest China . The Jinsha
River, which drops some 5,000 meters in elevation, represents
rich hydropower resources. Estimates indicate that the river
offers an easily exploitable generating capacity of 80 million kw,
making it China's largest untapped hydropower energy base.
</P>
<P>
Jin'anqiao is located in Lijiang county in the middle reaches
of the Jinsha River. A team from the Kunming Survey and Design
Institute under the Ministry of Power Industry began surveying the
proposed dam site in 1993 and has completed a preliminary
feasibility study.
</P>
<P>
Plans call for the installation of generators with a combined
generating capacity of three million kw. The projected cost of the
dam has been set at 12.08 billion yuan (1.47 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Highways, telecommunications and power supply facilities are
already in place for the construction of the project, according to
local officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
