<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shrimp Export To Earn 1.25 Bln Dollars in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The shrimp sector of Bangladesh
can earn 55 billion taka (about 1.25 billion U.S. dollars)
annually by exporting 90,000 tons of shrimps by the year 2002,
shrimp industry officials said today.
</P>
<P>
This target can be reached by the introduction of intensive
cultivation which could raise the per hectare yield to 300
kilograms from 250 kilograms under traditional system of
cultivation, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh exports 34,000 tons of shrimps annually,
 Gulam Mustafa, president of Bangladesh Frozen Food Exporters'
Association (BFFEA), was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The shrimp export industry started in early seventies, and at
the beginning earned about 630,000 dollars annually, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has attained tremendous success in exporting
cultivated shrimps on the world market in recent years, with
export increasing 28 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is now the 7th largest shrimp exporter in the world,
its income from shrimp export accounts for 10 percent of the total
export income and contributes 4.7 percent of its gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh earned 12.83 billion taka (about 290 million
dollars) from shrimp export in the 1995-96 fiscal year and is
expected to generate 13.66 billion taka (about 310 million
dollars) in fiscal 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
According to the BFFEA, the Bangladeshi Government has agreed
to give a special credit of 4 million taka (about 91,000 dollars)
for each shrimp-processing plant.
</P>
<P>
The major importers of Bangladesh shrimps are 15 European
countries, the U.S. and Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
