<HEADLINE> Aircraft Engine Overhaul Center Opened in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- An engine overhaul center
was opened here today to repair jumbo jets' engines for airlines
across the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Aero Engine Services Limited (HAESL), a 50-50
joint venture between Rolls-Royce and Hong Kong Aircraft
Engineering Company (HAECO), poured in 120 million U.S. dollars to
build the overhaul center at Tseung Kwan O Industrial Estate in
the northeast of the "New Territories."
</P>
<P>
The center can provide repair and overhaul services for
aircraft engines, ranging from the RB211 on the Boeing 757 to the
Trent 800 on the Boeing 777 and the V2500 engines on the Airbus
A320 and Boeing MD-90.
</P>
<P>
Inside the overhaul center is the largest engine test cell in
Asia, which is capable of testing the world's most powerful
engine, the Trent 800, which has been chosen to power all Boeing
777 jets ordered so far by Southeast Asian airlines.
</P>
<P>
Set up in June 1996, HAESL now shares HAECO's headquarters and
facilities at Kai Tak Airport. The company incorporated the engine
overhaul operations of its parent HAECO, which has 22-year
experience of maintaining Rolls-Royce engines.
</P>
<P>
The company will transfer all its facilities from Kai Tak to
Tseung Kwan O by April 1998, when the airport is scheduled to
close. The new overhaul center is expected to repair some 300
engines a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
