<HEADLINE> British Law Lords to Sit on HK Court of Final Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Lord Chancellor,
Lord Irvine of Lairg, announced here today that in principle two
serving British Law Lords can be made available to sit on Hong
Kong's Court of Final Appeal.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made in response to a request from Andrew
Li, the chief justice of Hong Kong, after a meeting between the
two this morning, according to a press release by the British
Consulate-General in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Further discussions will take place concerning potential
appointees.
</P>
<P>
Their appointments will be effected through the constitutional
processes of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and they
would form part of the court's non-permanent panel of judges.
</P>
<P>
"It has given great pleasure both to me and the chief justice
to have arrived at this important understanding," Lord Irvine
said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Li, in his statement, said he greatly welcomed
the announcement made by Lord Irvine.
</P>
<P>
"I shall continue discussion with him regarding potential
appointees before I put the matter to the Judicial Officers
Recommendation Commission," he said. "The commission will then
make recommendations to the chief executive and the constitutional
process for their appointment will then follow."
</P>
<P>
Lord Irvine, Britain's judicial chief, arrived in Hong Kong
yesterday for a five-day visit and he is the first high-ranking
government official from London since Hong Kong's return to China
on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
