<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Security Forces Nab 35 Militant Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security forces
arrested 35 Islamic militants overnight in a West Bank crackdown
on terrorism following the recent series of suicide bombings in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported today that Palestinian security forces
conducted house-to-house searches in West Bank towns Sunday night
to arrest activists associated with the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) and the Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
They were trying to find clues linking to the recent two
suicide bombing attacks in central Jerusalem in which 20 Israelis
and five suicide bombers were killed.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for both the July 30 twin
bombings in the Mahane Yehuda market, which killed 17 people and
wounded 170 others, and last Thursday's triple bombings in the Ben
Yehuda pedestrian mall, which claimed eight lives so far and
wounded 190 others.
</P>
<P>
The arrests came two days ahead of the much-awaited first
visit to the region by United States Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright on Wednesday, who has urged Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat to launch a war on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel has frozen the execution of the Oslo accords in a bid to
pressure Arafat to take "genuine steps" to fight Hamas and other
anti-Israeli militant organizations. Israeli government has
demanded Albright focus her attention on the PNA's fight on
terrorism during her visit here.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the PNA hopes Albright to persuade Israel to lift
the tough sanctions taken following the Ben Yehuda bombings,
including a total closure, the internal travel ban on West Bank
residents and the freeze on further troop redeployments.
</P>
<P>
The PNA actions against Islamic militants were regarded as a
gesture to the Americans ahead of Albright's trip to show that it
is making real efforts to crack down on terrorists.
</P>
<P>
But in a press conference held in Jerusalem this morning, PNA
Minister for Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini denied the latest
arrests were connected to Albright's coming visit.
</P>
<P>
He added that the PNA has high expectations for Albright's
visit, and hopes the U.S. would adopt an even-handed policy in
making efforts to get the peace process back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
