<HEADLINE> Jordan Minister Terms Tripartite Summit As Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official
today termed the summit held here Sunday among Egyptian, Jordanian
and Palestinian leaders as important to coordinate Arab stances.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs
Radio, Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Services and
Administrative Development Abdullah Ensour said the meeting was a
"sound step" by the Arab leaders to coordinate their stances on the
current developments.
</P>
<P>
The summit among Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, King Hussein
of Jordan and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was held to prepare
for the upcoming tour of the Mideast by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, said the minister, who attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
"Their response to Albright's views and initiatives will be
coordinated and orchestrated," he said, adding that "this
unanimity in views" was the target of Sunday's summit.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, the three leaders called on the U.S. to redouble
its effort to save peace and urged parties concerned to
"accurately and honestly" implement all signed accords, according
to the statement issued at the end of the nearly three-hour
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Albright is reportedly to be on a week-long trip to Israel,
Palestinian areas, Jordan, Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia starting
Wednesday in a bid to revive the stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace
negotiations which came to a halt since Israel began construction
of a controversial Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in
March.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only two Arab countries that have
diplomatic ties with Israel and played important roles in past
mediation in Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
