<HEADLINE> Nigerian Administrator Backs Abacha's Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The military administrator of
Kano State in north Nigeria, Colonel Dominic Oneya said recently
that he supports General Sani Abacha's presidency.
</P>
<P>
Oneya thus became the second man of the 30 administrators that
have declared his support to the head of state's candidacy if he
choose to contest in next year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Mohammed Marwa, the administrator of Lagos State in
the southwest expressed the same position a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a forum sponsored by the official New Nigerian
newspaper, Colonel Oneya said General Abacha is free to aspire to
the presidency of the nation through a free and fair election.
</P>
<P>
"If he desires to contest any elective office, I will give him
my support being a citizen of Kano," he said.
</P>
<P>
Oneya, however, accused those canvassing for Abacha's
presidency of having their own program.
</P>
<P>
As the military head of state he ushered in the current
transition to civil rule program, Abacha's qualification as a
presidency candidate have been questioned by some people both in
and outside Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
A recent research done by scholars from a group of Nigerian
universities, however, claimed that 72 percent of Nigerians
support Abacha's presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
