<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Starts With Stressing on Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) started their
summit here in the southern Malawi city this morning, putting
integration as the top agenda.
</P>
<P>
Bakili Muluzi, President of the Republic of Malawi, said at the
opening ceremony that the group is aimed at "true and meaningful
integration to the benefit of the people in the region."
</P>
<P>
High on the development agenda at the summit will be put on
gender, energy, productivity, health, environment, natural
resources management, human resources development, good
governance and popular participation, said Muluzi.
</P>
<P>
The challenges SADC faces are to eradicate poverty and promote
development, he said, adding that institutional mechanisms are in
place to guarantee the future prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The SADC members need to consolidate the already achieved
democracy and good governance for free enterprise, human
resources development and harmonious labor management relations,
Muluzi said.
</P>
<P>
Particular attention to the development of small and medium
scale enterprises, the informal sector and the small-holder
agriculture sector, as these sectors offer real prospects for
gains in productivity, the Malawian leader said.
</P>
<P>
Food security in the region, where food production has
declined for the serious drought and migratory pests, is yet
another challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
More emphasis is stressed by the Malawian leader on policies
and programs that will enable the region to achieve food
self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
Peace and stability, democracy and respect for human rights,
which continue to deepen in the region, is of crucial importance,
without which no significant social or economic development can
be achieved, Muluzi said.
</P>
<P>
Ten heads of state of the 12 SADC members, except Angola which
sent its minister of construction De Castro Vandunen, and Lesotho
representing by its deputy Prime Minister Pakalltha B. Mosisili,
are attending the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
