<HEADLINE> South Asian Tourism Ministers to Meet in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tourism ministers of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) are to meet on
September 23 and 24 in Colombo of Sri Lanka, the Information
Department said in a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from Bangladesh, Bhutan, Pakistan, the Maldives,
Nepal, India and Sri Lanka will discuss ways of promoting this
region's tourism industry in the conference.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was previously scheduled for April 25 and 26 but it
was later canceled.
</P>
<P>
The last meeting of its kind was held 28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the ministers will adopt some major
policies that will facilitate the region's tourism development.
</P>
<P>
On the top of their agenda are the issues of simplifying visa
related procedures and documentation for nationals of SAARC
countries and establishment of direct air links between SAARC
capitals.
</P>
<P>
Special air fare within the region will also be introduced on
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will avail themselves of this convention to
explore the possibility of the convertibility of SAARC currencies
and study strategies in promoting South Asia as a
multi-destination.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985 to promote regional cooperation
in economic, social, cultural and technological fields, has a
combined population of one billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
