<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Concerned About Mideast Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has expressed concern over the deteriorating situation in
the Middle East, a statement issued by the U.N. office said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The statement on U.N. activities in hotbeds of conflict came
four days after the triple suicide bombing in Jerusalem which
killed eight people and wounded nearly 200 others.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who deemed the Mideast to be among the most tense areas
in the world, voiced hope that the Palestinian-Israeli sides, the
focal point of Arab-Israeli conflict, would resume their peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been stalled since
March when Israel broke ground for a new Jewish settlement in
traditional Arab East Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as
their future capital.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. chief also expressed deep concern over the current
Lebanese-Israeli conflicts in south Lebanon and of the conflicts
between Iraq and Kuwait," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in the region escalated after 11 Israeli commandos
were killed last Friday in a fierce clash with Iranian-backed
Hezbollah guerrillas and the Lebanese army in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Iraq-Kuwait Observers Mission (UNIKOM) was working to
achieve security and stability on the borders between the two
countries, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990 and later was driven out by
U.S.-led multi-national forces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan spoke of the U.N.'s contributions to bolster
security and stability in the region and cited as an example the
humanitarian aid dispensed by the United Nations Works and Relief
Agency (UNWRA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
