<HEADLINE> Taliban Gain Territory in Northern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Forces loyal to the Afghan
Taliban militia have expanded their enclave of territory in
northern Afghanistan and edged closer to the stronghold of their
rival alliance, Taliban sources said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban fighters have taken the town of Tashqurghan, about 40
km east of Mazar-e-Sharif, capital of Afghanistan's northwestern
Balkh province, with the help of some defected local commanders,
the Taliban sources here said.
</P>
<P>
However, there have been no reports of casualties and no exact
information on how much ground has been lost by the anti-Taliban
alliance, based in Mazar-e-Sharif and led mainly by Uzbek warlord
Abdul Malik and Tajik warlord Ahmad Masood.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to launch counter-attacks, Malik has already cut
the main road between Mazar-e-Sharif and areas north of Kabul and
rushed more forces to the front, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been raging for many days near the border of
Malik-controlled provinces of Balkh and Samangan as well as Kunduz
province which has been held by a Taliban expeditionary force
since late May.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban forces under Masood's command have been also
battling the Islamic militia north of Kabul. Despite sporadic
battles and frequent bombing raids, the front lines between the
two sides have remained deadlocked around 25 km north of Kabul for
more than two months.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who control the Afghan capital of Kabul and
two-thirds of Afghanistan's territory, have vowed to impose a
strict Islamic law in the war-torn country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
