<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Denies Financial Problems in Banking System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Philippine banking
official today strongly denied reports that some big banks are
experiencing financial problems as a result of the current turmoil
in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson, governor of the Philippine Central Bank, said
in a statement that he will seek the help of the National Bureau
of Investigation (NBI) to find out the veracity of these reports.
</P>
<P>
He said necessary action will be taken against those who are
responsible for spreading such rumors that the banking system is
indeed in trouble.
</P>
<P>
These stories are absolutely baseless and irresponsible
considering that the banking industry at the moment is in fact in
robust health, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the central bank is currently monitoring the
performance of individual banks, particularly the commercial
banks, so that there is no reason to be alarmed by these rumors.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that bank capitals are adequate to meet
international business standard, adding that the banking industry
has been raking in huge profits.
</P>
<P>
He assured the public, particularly the millions of depositors,
not to be alarmed by the rumors which were spread by people whose
motives could result in panic withdrawals thus adding misery to
the currency crisis which the financial market is experiencing at
the moment.
</P>
<P>
Singson added that the central bank is always on standby and
ready to come to the rescue of banks which need assistance as
allowed by law in the event the situation gets out of control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
