<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Calls for Struggling Against Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
here today called on various countries in the world to struggle
against poverty.
</P>
<P>
Opening the regional conference on comparative experience in
poverty eradication at the State Palace, the president said
poverty eradication is the great challenge of man and mankind at
the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Poverty is a major problem of developing countries in many
parts of the world, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto quoted the United Nations report as saying that today
there are more than 1.3 billion poor people on the face of our
planet. The ranks of these poor people continue to become larger
by around 25 million every year.
</P>
<P>
"Our hearts become growingly painful, because this figure shows
that the number of our poor fellow human beings increases by 47
persons every minute," he said.
</P>
<P>
On economy and poverty eradication in Indonesia, Soeharto said
after long years of hard work, Indonesia succeeded in drastically
reducing the number of poor people.
</P>
<P>
In 1970, Indonesia's poor population was 70 million persons, or
60 percent of the total population. In 1996, the number declined
to around 20 million or 11 percent of the population. During that
period of 26 years, Indonesia's population rose by 84 million,
from 116 million in 1970 to 200 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto pointed out that development is a process of
large-scale changes. They must be aimed at the improvement and
advancement of people's life. That should be planned with a clear
vision to ensure that dynamic forces of the nation become the
motor of development.
</P>
<P>
To this end, he said, national development necessitates a solid
and dynamic national stability in all aspects of life. Such
stability shall induce an adequate economic growth and this, in
turn, shall materialize equitable distribution of development
which is imbued with social justice and this is conducive to the
improvement of the people's well-being and enhancement of human
dignity.
</P>
<P>
"Unless there is growth, there will never be an improved
prosperity. The absence of an equitable distribution may become
the seed of social unrest that will lead to social upheaval and
disintegration," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting is attended by representatives from 15
countries, including China.
</P>
<P>
Before the opening of the meeting, President Soeharto received
a special citation presented personally by the administrator of
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) for Indonesia's
success in reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a president receives a UNDP award,
official sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Enforce Anti-dumping Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan government is
considering the enforcement of an anti-dumping law to protect the
country's national industries, sources close to the Commerce
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The anti-dumping law, which has already been drafted by the
National Tariff Commission, is likely to be enforced along with
the forthcoming industrial policy as part of the continuous
process of economic reforms initiated by the government led by
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
It is deemed necessary for Pakistan to enforce such a law to
protect the local industry when the country's products are being
hit hard by anti-dumping laws in Japan and European countries,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Through various means, and especially smuggling, goods are
being dumped in Pakistan in relatively cheaper prices creating
unfair competition for the local industry, they said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, which is awaiting adoption by the
parliament, punitive duties have been proposed for dumping and
subsidization of goods from other countries, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
These punitive duties could remain enforced for a minimum
period of five years and, in some cases if necessary, this period
can be extended, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
