<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Manufacturing Output Up 7.7 Pct in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing
output increased 7.7 percent in July with higher output of
chemical products and continued recovery in the electronics
industry, the Economic Development Board (EDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in 1997, the cumulative output of the
manufacturing sector has turned positive, recording a marginal
increase of 0.2 percent over the same period of last year, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The chemicals industries, including petroleum, petrochemicals,
pharmaceuticals and industries/specialty chemicals, continued to
expand, as the July increase of 34.4 percent brought the
cumulative output growth of the first seven months of 1997 to 13.2
percent, the EDB said.
</P>
<P>
The output of the electronics industry was sustained by the
continued export demand, the EDB said, noting that July saw an
increase of 9.1 percent in output arising from higher output of
disk drives, computer peripherals, semiconductors and
telecommunication equipment.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative output for the first seven months of 1997 was
now 1.1 percent less than the same 1996 period, it said.
</P>
<P>
The electrical machinery industry grew 7.1 percent as output of
connectors, power cables and batteries increased to meet export
orders. The cumulative output for the first seven months of this
year was 0.5 percent lower than the corresponding period of last
year, the EDB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
