<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Promotes Use of Unleaded Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's economic
powerhouse, recently announced a decision to require all local
vehicles to use unleaded gas effective October 1.
</P>
<P>
The city introduced the new regulation as part of its
efforts to improve environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation will require the use of unleaded gas in all
vehicles, including automobiles, motorized bicycles and
motorcycles operating in urban and rural areas. In addition, the
city's service stations will be required to sell lead-free gas,
according to a Monday conference focusing on the promotion of
unleaded gas.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Environmental Protection Bureau, the Administration
for Industry and Commerce and the Bureau for Technology
Supervision will monitor implementation of the program requiring
the use of unleaded gasoline.
</P>
<P>
Those found in violation of the regulation will be subject to
severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is currently home to more than 1.3 million vehicles,
some 98.5 percent of them use leaded gasoline. Exhaust emissions are
currently a serious problem creating environmental
pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
