<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberian Currency Appreciates Against US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian currency called
"Liberty" has gained 33 percent against the U.S. Dollar in the
country's flourishing parallel money market since the election in
July, the Vanguard newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said, Liberty, which exchanged at an average of 45
for one Dollar before the July 19 election, rose to 30 for one
greenback by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Liberty was at par with the U.S. Dollar in circulation in
Liberia before it was changed in 1985 by late President Samuel
Doe.
</P>
<P>
Although the appreciation has yet to reflect the price of
goods and the shattered lives of average Liberians, economists
say the trend, if maintained, could put Liberia on the way to
economic recovery after the war.
</P>
<P>
A stronger parallel currency, the JJ Roberts Liberian Dollar,
used in the former strong hold of Charles Taylor's National
Patriotic Front-line, is also now at par with Liberty. The
exchange rate used to be three Liberty to one JJ before the
election.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said during his election campaign that he would restore
the U.S. Dollar as the legal tender in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
