<HEADLINE> Thai Opposition Lodges No-Confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Thai opposition today
submitted a no-confidence motion to the parliament, accusing the
current government of mis-managing the country's economy and
pushing it to the edge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
The motion, co-signed by 88 of the total 172 house members of
five opposition parties, was presented to the parliament by
opposition leader Chuan Leekpai of the Democratic Party this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The one-page motion accuses Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh and his nine-month-old administration for failing to
ease the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wan Muhamad Nor Matha, speaker of the lower house, said the
parliament would likely debate on the motion on September 24-25.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit earlier expressed hopes that the parliament would open
the debate as early as possible so that he could focus his
attention on solving the country's economic problems. 
</P>
