<HEADLINE> International Literacy Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi president and prime
minister issued separate messages today to observe the
International Literacy Day which falls on today, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
President Shahabuddin Ahmed said in his message that the
government has fixed target to lower the rate of illiteracy to 62
percent from over 70 percent by the year 2000, the newspaper The
Financial Express said.
</P>
<P>
The president stated in his message that there is no
alternative to development of human resources for the overall
progress of the country. He called upon all irrespective of party
and opinions to make concerted efforts to build up an educated
class.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi Government has taken the task of eradicating
illiteracy in the country as part of its constitutional obligation
and political commitment, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said in her
message published by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We have no alternative to educating the people within the
short possible time to attain overall development of the country,"
the prime minister said, adding that her government is doing its
utmost to achieve the goal set in her election manifesto to remove
illiteracy within ten years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
