<HEADLINE> Former Champion Fittipaldi Hurt in Light Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Former world motor racing
champion Emerson Fittipaldi injured his back when he crashed a
micro-light plane at his farm at Araquara, 300km from Sao Paulo,
police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
A local report said Fittipaldi had broken a vertebrae and could
be paralysed. His six-year-old son Lucas, who was a passenger, was
unhurt.
</P>
<P>
Fittipaldi and his son were found 11 hours after taking off by
a search party in marsh land.
</P>
<P>
Fittipaldi, 50, became the youngest ever formula one world
champion at 25 in 1972. He reclaimed the title in 1974 driving for
McLaren.
</P>
<P>
He retired from formula one grand prix driving in 1980 and in
his 40s went into Indycar racing, winning the Indianapolis 500 in
1989 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian gave up racing after suffering a neck injury in
the Michigan Indycar race a year ago. 
</P>
