<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Repulse Rebel Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 people, including
seven civilians, were killed in northeastern Sri Lanka today as
government troops repulsed a massive Tamil guerrilla attack, a
military spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A large group of Tamil rebels attacked the Kalyanapura village
in Welioya at around 1:30 a.m. Government troops guarding the
village fired back, causing heavy casualties of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman for the Defense Ministry put the death
toll at 14, including seven rebels and seven civilians in the
village.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of gunfire also caused four government soldiers
and five civilians injured.
</P>
<P>
Searching the battlefield, the troops recovered two light
machine guns, five T-56 weapons and other military items left
behind by the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The renewed fighting came two days after the temporary truce
between the two sides collapsed in the east of the country on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamils Eelam (LTTE) has been fighting
for a separate state of their own for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
So far the bitter war has claimed more than 50,000 lives and
hindered economic development of this island nation.
</P>
<P>
Trying to bring an end to the war, the government has proposed
to solve the long-standing conflict through political ways, but
the Tamil rebels simply gave a definite "no" answer by staging one
after another attacks at government and military targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
