<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Australian Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu
Rongji met with Australian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Trade Tim Fischer here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu extended a warm welcome to Fischer who is visiting China
for the second time since assuming office.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Australian relations have maintained excellent momentum
for development, with leaders from both countries exchanging
frequent visits and maintaining close contact. All this, Zhu
added, has played a positive role in stimulating bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that China and Australia are currently trade and
investment partners, and pointed to the fruitful results in
cooperation in areas including the military, scientific,
technological, cultural and educational sectors.
</P>
<P>
Zhu stressed that China pursues mutually beneficial cooperation
with Australia in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said that Zhu's recent successful visit to Australia
helped advance bilateral ties. He reiterated that Australia pays
great attention to its relations with China, and considers such
relations as an extremely important aspect of the nation's foreign
relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Australian government fully recognizes that
China is playing an extremely important role in the Asia-Pacific
Region, and is totally willing to establish a long-term
cooperative economic and trade partnership with China to raise
bilateral ties to a new plateau. Fischer also reaffirmed
Australia's adherence to the "One China" policy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Hong Kong's return to the motherland has been
accompanied by stability in various areas, including the new
adminstrative region's financial sector and stock market. For
this, Fischer congratulated the Chinese government on behalf of
the Australian government.
</P>
<P>
Zhu spoke highly of Australia's position regarding the "One
China" policy and its stress on relations with China. He expressed
appreciation for Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer's
participation in Hong Kong hand-over ceremonies, including the
swearing-in of the Provisional Legislative Council. Zhu also
pointed to Fischer's participation in related ceremonies held by
the Chinese embassy in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed the issue of China's entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO), with both agreeing that bilateral
negotiations have achieved important progress, and both sides are
willing to maintain a constructive attitude and strive for an
early agreement. Fischer stressed that Australia supports China's
entry into the WTO,
</P>
<P>
Fischer arrived in Beijing earlier today as guest of
Zhu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
