<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Vows to Push on Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto vowed today to push through his pledged reforms hours
after he was reelected president of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
"Reforms in six fields will accompany the very difficult
decision to conduct a thorough probe into our conventional systems
and vested interests," Hashimoto told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto has pledged to carry out reforms in administration,
fiscal policy, economic structure, social welfare, finance and
education.
</P>
<P>
Such reforms will require some initial sacrifices and a strong
and stable political foundation is therefore essential, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he will make efforts to further improve
relations with China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, 60, is the first LDP president in 13 years to get a
second two-year term since former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasono
in November 1984.
</P>
<P>
His reelection will be formally endorsed at a plenary session
of the LDP members in both houses of the Diet (parliament)
scheduled for Thursday. After that, he is expected to name key
party posts and reshuffle the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto was first elected LDP president in September 1995 in
an overwhelming victory over his sole rival, Junichiro Koizumi,
the current health and welfare minister.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto took the helm of a coalition government of the LDP,
Social Democratic Party (SDP) and Sakigake in January 1996 from
Tomiichi Murayama, head of the SDP, and launched his second
cabinet in last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
