<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Ramos Denies Seeking to Scrap 1998 Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos, in a fresh move to ease public anxieties, today vehemently
rejected charges that he is seeking to scrap the 1998 general
election and proclaim martial law in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Ramos administration and I as president have been the
subject of a massive disinformation campaign on various issues
related to constitutional change," Ramos said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"There are some people who maliciously claim that we are
planning no elections in May 1998, that we are seeking to proclaim
martial law, that we are veering toward dictatorship."
</P>
<P>
Slamming these claims as "blatant lies, falsehoods and
fabrications," Ramos said, "As president, I categorically and
emphatically deny these irresponsible accusations."
</P>
<P>
"I also categorically declare that our country will definitely
have national and local elections in May 1998 as scheduled," he
said, adding that he is against "term extension."
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Ramos to formally dismiss
accusations that he is planning to seek a second term by imposing
martial law and other means.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' statement came two days after wide anxieties were
generated among the church, the opposition camp and the business
community by the president's remarks at an economic meeting last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Ramos surprised many by announcing that he must
"keep his options open" -- remarks which were widely interpreted
as a hint that Ramos was open for another term under a changed
charter.
</P>
<P>
But on Saturday, Ramos brushed aside such speculations by
saying his option is to choose his successor in his ruling party
for next year's polls.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition accused the Ramos administration of
creating political instability by planting bombs in public places
to provide an excuse for imposing martial law.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, two separate bomb blasts in Manila killed six
people and wounded 60 others. A shadowy military group claimed
responsibility for the bombings, saying it supports a second term
for Ramos and threatening more offensives if opposition to Ramos'
re-election persists.
</P>
<P>
In today's statement, Ramos said he has "no intention
whatsoever to proclaim martial law" and will not direct the
military to "undertake any operations that may be misconstrued as
actions leading to martial law."
</P>
<P>
Ramos also stressed that his record stands against
dictatorship, citing his role in the 1986 people power revolution
which ended the dictatorial rule of former President Ferdinand
Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's 1987 constitution, Ramos must step down in
June 1998 when his single six-year term expires. But his
supporters have sought to revise the charter to lift term limits
for the president since last year.
</P>
<P>
The constitution, promulgated after the ouster of former
President Marcos, provides for only one single six-year term for
the president in order to prevent a repeat of dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has repeatedly voiced his determination to step down in
June 1998 when his six-year term expires. But he also expressed
strong support for the people's right to rewrite the constitution.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
