<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Beefs up Security for More Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces
have been on high alert against new terror attacks before or
during U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's visit this
Wednesday, The Jerusalem Post newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Since last Thursday's triple suicide bombing in Jerusalem's
Ben Yehuda Street, which killed eight people (including the three
bombers) and wounded nearly 200 others, Israeli security forces
have arrested 169 Palestinians in the West Bank as suspects of the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials claimed that the July 30 Mahaneh Yehuda and
September 4 Ben Yehuda bombings were both carried out by Hamas
members from the West Bank or Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Following the Ben Yehuda attack, Israel reimposed a complete
closure on West Bank and Gaza Strip and demanded all Palestinian
workers inside Israel return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
In addition, restrictions on internal movements were ordered on
villages and towns under Palestinian control. Israelis were also
barred from entering these areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel meanwhile demanded Sunday that the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) extradite Palestinian police chief Ghazi Jabali
for questioning about his suspected involvement in "a conspiracy
to commit crime and attempted murder."
</P>
<P>
Israeli justice officials charged that Jabali was suspected of
involvement in a shooting in July at a Jewish settler's car which
caused no injury. But Jabali and the PNA have denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
On its part, the PNA links security ties with Israel to
further withdrawals of Israeli troops from West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Dahlan, chief of the PNA's Preventive Security
Apparatus in Gaza Strip, said he was prepared to cooperate with
Israel "on condition that it participates in the peace process.
This means the implementation of the interim agreements signed
until now."
</P>
<P>
Albright will arrive to begin her first Middle East trip
Wednesday in an effort to revive the deep-troubled peace process
and restore confidence between Israel and Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
