<HEADLINE> Coca-cola Invests in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Coca-cola company,
the world's leading soft drinks group, would today sign a joint
venture agreement with the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, a new bottling plant will be established and
the existing one will be upgraded, according to local media
reports.
</P>
<P>
The investment in the two plants, which would be managed by
South African Breweries, would total about 33 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The pact would be signed, at a meeting ending the three-day
U.S.-Angolan trade mission, by Angolan President Eduardo Dos
Santos and Coca-cola's African President Carl Ware.
</P>
<P>
Coca cola's African spokesman said the joint venture formed
part of his company's belief in Angola's future and that of its
people.
</P>
<P>
Coca-cola's move into Angola follows hard on the heels of
similar investment in Mozambique, Zimbabwe, South Africa and east
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Coca-cola and its bottling partners employ 100,000 people in
Africa now, of which 13,000 are in South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
