<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition-Sponsored Rally Flops in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A planned rally called by the
National Convention Executive Council (NCEC) in Kisumu, the
third-largest city of Kenya, flopped Sunday when nine Opposition
leaders were detained at Kisumu airport.
</P>
<P>
The much-publicized rally in the city ashore Lake Victoria
failed to take off as anti-riot police, patrolling the streets in
armored cars or on foot, ensured no gatherings were held or no
groups of people met to discuss the meeting, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Security was tight in the town and its outskirts since
Saturday evening. The meeting venue was guarded overnight with
squads of officers pitching tents there so that nobody could
enter.
</P>
<P>
Among the Opposition leaders having been held at the airport
for six hours were FORD-Kenya First National Vice-Chairman James
Orengo, NCEC leader Kivutha Kibwana and former minister Onyango
Midika. They boarded a return flight here on yesterday evening.
</P>
<P>
However, traders allegedly lost business worth millions of
Shillings after police broke up a packed Kibuye market in Kisumu
as they clamped down on Opposition supporters, said the press
reports.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC rally came after the formation of an inter-parties
parliamental group, comprising lawmakers from both the ruling
Kenya African National Union and the Opposition on minimum
constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC has dismissed the group's work and called national
strikes and demonstrations on September 17-18 and October 8-9 to
press the government for total constitutional reforms before the
general elections to be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
But 17 foreign embassies, mainly from western countries,
announced Saturday their support for the parliamental group.
which is to hold a plenary meeting Tuesday on reforms.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, KANU reiterated it will not hold dialogue with the
NCEC as the latter is unregistered, insisting that the reforms
talks should only be undertaken within legal framework.
</P>
<P>
KANU will open its National Delegate Conference on September
16 over reform talks and the forthcoming general elections. At
the KANU conference before the first multi-party election in
1992, Moi was elected as KANU's sole presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Political atmosphere has been tightening in the country
following several rounds of violent clashes between the
government and the Opposition since May, the key loan cut by the
International Monetary Fund and killings on the Coast.
</P>
<P>
Moi has recently claimed time and again that he would announce
the poll date soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
