<HEADLINE> Wildlife College Opens in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Wildlife College, the first of its kind in the region, was
launched in Northern Province, South Africa at the weekend, local
daily Sowetan reported today.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the wildlife college was a historical
milestone for conservation, Environmental and Tourism Affairs
Minister Pallo Jordan was quoted as making a report at the
opening of the 5.1-million U.S. Dollars college.
</P>
<P>
The project of the World Wildlife Federation, Jordan said, was
aimed at giving advance education and training to protected
wildlife area managers from all over southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The college, situated near the Kruger national park's Orpen
gate, Northern province, was built through grants from the
German, Danish and Norwegian government, and more than 30 South
African donors.
</P>
<P>
Students from Kenya, Uganda, Namibia and Lesotho have already
attended the school, while Malawi, Mauritius and Cote d'Ivoire
were reportedly keen to send their game rangers to the college.
</P>
</TEXT>
