<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Strengthens Democratic Awareness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Village and residential
committees, the public servant system, and people's congress at
all levels provide effective mediums for the Chinese people to
play a more active role in public life.
</P>
<P>
Liu Junnin, a political researcher with the China Academy of
Social Sciences noted that "economic prosperity has cultivated
growing enthusiasm for political participation on the part of
Chinese people, and has indeed sparked a burgeoning democratic
awareness."
</P>
<P>
Economic reforms China adopted since the late 1970s have
encouraged the people to gain wealth through hard work and honest
labor. The country's market economy is striving to open more
options to enhance lifestyles and employment opportunities for the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in rural China, areas which spearheaded economic
reform, directly elect committees to administer daily affairs in
their respective villages, with voter turnout standing at around
90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most villages have introduced the system of village
representative meetings which not only ensure that farmers have a
say in matters directly relating to lives, but also provide an
opportunity for local residents to listen to reports on village
budget management.
</P>
<P>
Similar changes can be found in state enterprises where workers
supervise the management and daily operation through workers
representative meetings.
</P>
<P>
Workers' organizations in some areas directly elect factory
directors and managers, and workers are themselves elected to
serve on board of directors or supervisory commissions.
</P>
<P>
A more transparent public servant system has emerged along with
the deepening of reforms. The State Council decree issued in 1993
stipulates that government functionaries be recruited through open
and fair competitions.
</P>
<P>
Mayor in major cities such as Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai
have established special hotlines to enable local residents to
offers suggestions or lodge complaints.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980s, the country has promulgated a law on the
organization of village committees, a law on urban residential
committees and a new law governing the election of deputies to
people's congresses.
</P>
<P>
More than 650,000 representatives at county level are preparing
for the election of new local people's congresses. Voters will be
able to participate in direct elections offering a large slate of
candidates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman FM Starts Two-Day Visit to Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Omani Foreign Minister
Yousef bin Alawi arrived here today for a two-day visit to
Pakistan with the aim to enhance bilateral economic relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan and Oman have a lot of possibilities for
strengthening the bilateral economic relations specially in areas
of trade and investment," Yousef said at a brief news conference
upon his arrival at the airport here.
</P>
<P>
On the Kashmir issue, Yousef said Oman supports Pak-Indian
dialogue for the settlement of the issue and other outstanding
issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We understand the Kashmir issue should be solved through
negotiations and being neighbor of the two countries our role in
this will be constructive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Afghan situation, Yousef underscored that the
Afghan issue needs to be addressed urgently for development in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"All nations in the region should work for peace in
Afghanistan, and as for Oman, we will extend all possible
assistance in materializing peace in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Pakistan, the Omani foreign minister will
call on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, President Farooq Leghari and
other senior officials in charge of economic and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Pakistan and Oman has been growing in the last
two years. Exports from Pakistan to Oman grew by 9.53 million U.S.
dollars between July 1995 to March 1996 and July 1996 to March
1997, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
A number of projects have also been under discussion including
the setting up of a Pakistan-Oman Joint Holding Company which will
provide a framework and modalities for strengthening economic
cooperation between the two countries, officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
