<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos Monday bluntly
denied accusations that his administration is planning to scrap
the 1998 general polls and seeking to proclaim martial law in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"There are some people who maliciously claim that we are
planning no elections in May 1998, that we are seeking to proclaim
martial law, that we are veering toward dictatorship," Ramos said
in a statement. (Philippines-Ramos-Denial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto Monday was
reelected unchallengedly for a second term as the president of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
His reelection will be formally endorsed at a plenary session
of the LDP members in both houses of the Diet (parliament)
scheduled for Thursday. After that, he is expected to name key
party posts and reshuffle the cabinet. (Japan-Hashimoto-Reelection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai health officials in Surin province in
northeastern Thailand are warning that malaria may spread at a
temporary Cambodian refugee camp in the province's Kap Choeng
district, the local press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The increasing number of malaria patients were reportedly due
to the rainy season and cross border travels, especially the
influx of Cambodian refugees who escaped the recent fighting in
their country. (Thailand-Cambodia-Malaria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- A fairly strong earthquake registering 5.2 on the
Richter scale jolted the Kanto and Izu areas in eastern Japan
Monday morning, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
But there were no immediate reports about damage or injuries.
The quake occurred at 8:40 a.m. local time and the epicenter was
about 110 kilometers underground in Tokyo Bay. (Japan-Quake)
</P>
