<HEADLINE> China's First Marine High-Tech Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Tanggu Marine Development
Zone of Tianjin is the first state-level zone of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
The local management committee reports that the zone has
approved the establishment of more than 900 enterprises, including
300 foreign-funded businesses involving over 500 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 businesses have commenced construction in the zone,
with a number having already entered operations. In addition, the
zone has also sold land-use rights for one square kilometer.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the zone commenced in 1993 and it was approved
as a state-level development zone in 1995. First phase
construction in the zone will cover 4.5 sq km of mostly barren
hills and salt pans.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure construction on two sq km has been completed
over the past five years
</P>
<P>
The zone, which will basically focus on development of the
marine industry, has established a service agency under the
National Bureau of Oceanography. The agency will be responsible
for the promotion of turning scientific and technological
achievements into production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First National Investment And Trade Fair Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China's First National
Investment and Trade Fair opened today in Xiamen, a port city of
East China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The fair, jointly sponsored by the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) and the Fujian provincial and
Xiamen city governments, is the country's first national investment
promotion event designed to attract direct investment from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
The fair will focus on attracting foreign investment from
across the world and promoting trade of products manufactured by
joint ventures and foreign-funded enterprises, according to MOFTEC
Vice-Minister Sun Zhenyu.
</P>
<P>
The fair will also feature various exhibitions aiming at
enhancing economic cooperation and trade across the Taiwan
Straits, said Sun.
</P>
<P>
The 37 exhibition halls of the fair will offer a series of
investment projects related to the high-tech sectors and basic
industries, as well as projects in infrastructure and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He added that the fair will also offer famous high quality
products manufactured in Hong Kong, Taiwan and some foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the fair are representatives from coastal,
border and riparian areas, as well as those from central and
western provinces. The event will, in fact, represent a cross
section of the nation, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
He said the fair will demonstrate the emergence of a new
pattern with coastal special economic zones as the vanguard, along
with the participation of ministries and provinces, and the
balanced development of eastern and western provinces.
</P>
<P>
Sun emphasized that upgrading the originally Fujian provincial
investment fair to a national event will further raise the
effectiveness, quality and level in the use of overseas
investment. He said the fair will guide and regulate various local
events to introduce investment, facilitate direct contacts between
overseas investors and China's provinces and municipalities, and
gradually alter the practice of sending large delegations overseas
to attract investment.
</P>
<P>
Some 161 delegations consisting of 5,000 businessmen from 27
countries and regions have been here to participate in the fair,
including over 70 delegations from developed countries, and 20
delegations from major transnational corporations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Grants Uganda Sum to Help Reduce Its Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain has decided to grant
Uganda over 6.5 million Pounds (10.5 million US Dollars) to help
reduce its debts burden to the African Development Bank, reported
the local media today.
</P>
<P>
British High Commissioner to Uganda M. Cook confirmed this to
Ugandan Finance Minister Mayanja Nkangi last week.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
agreed on the heavily indebted poor countries (HIPC) initiative
which, together with regional development banks will reduce the
value of their outstanding loans to eligible countries.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to bring about a once and for all reduction in the
debts of the poorest countries to level that is affordable.
</P>
<P>
Uganda will be the first country to benefit under the HIPC
initiative, having pursued sound economic policies for some 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Britain's bilateral contribution of 10.5 million U.S. Dollars
together with other donor contribution means that the full cost
of reducing Uganda's debt to African Development Bank can now be
met.
</P>
<P>
The grant is in addition to Britain's existing 40 million
Pound (64 million US Dollars) aid program to Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shangdong Expands Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province in east China
recorded total exports of 45.2 billion US dollars for the period
from 1992 to the end of June this year, with the average annual
increase of 23 percent, far above the national average.
</P>
<P>
The province's 1996 exports hit 17.8 billion US dollars, a
three-fold increase on 1992. Manufactured goods accounted for 76
percent of total exports, up from 50 percent in the early
1990s. Shandong currently exports products to 180 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
The province has approved 17,800 foreign-funded enterprises
over the past five years. Total contracted investments hit 24.8
billion US dollars, or 21 times the total for the period prior to
1991. Some 910 of the enterprises involved investments of over 10
million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 of the world's top 500 multinational corporations
have conducted operations in the province.
</P>
<P>
Shandong also recorded average annual growth of more than 60
percent in project contract and labor services in overseas markets
during the period. The province has recorded a total related
business volume of 825 million US dollars, with the sector
currently employing 54,000 laborers.
</P>
<P>
Shandong has established 370 businesses in 60 countries and
regions, up 38-fold on the early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
