<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Families Eager To Buy Larger Color TV Sets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Most families in Shanghai,
China's largest and most developed industrial city, are rapidly
replacing small screen color television sets with advanced
multifunctional units.
</P>
<P>
According to recent surveys conducted by local banks and
government departments in charge of commerce, some 71.36 percent
of respondents indicated a desire to purchase new, with 56.2
percent indicating a preference for 29 inch screens, 28.1 percent
for 25 inch screens, 8.7 percent for screens measuring 21 inches,
and 4.4 percent for 34 inches.
</P>
<P>
In addition, an increasing number of local residents expressed
their preference for domestic products. Some 62 percent of
respondents noted that they will purchase
domestically-manufactured televisions withing the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Every 100 families in Shanghai currently own an average of
110.65 color television sets, the majority of which are 21 inch
set purchased in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Most families cite the fact that although their old sets are
still workable, they provide access to fewer channels, have small
screens and lack remote control, karaoke and VCD capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Improved living standards have also contributed to expanding
desire for state-of-the-art television sets. Moreover, falling
prices and efforts by manufacturers and dealers to improve
services have contributed to the increasing sales volume for color
television sets.
</P>
<P>
Prices on the local market have, in fact, dropped by around 30
percent over the past two years alone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
