<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Bans Kenya Airline in Row over Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- African Airlines
International (AAI), a private Kenyan carrier, has been banned
from Tanzanian air-space because it made a sanctions-busting
flight to Burundi, the East African weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Tanzanian Foreign Ministry said his
ministry banned last week any further flights by the AAI through
Tanzanian air-space under the sanctions agreement. The airline
flew from Nairobi to Bujumbura on July 17.
</P>
<P>
It appeared the airline had deliberately tried to mislead
Tanzania about its destination by lying it was going to the
Democratic Republic of Congo at the time, the spokesman said,
adding the ban is indefinite.
</P>
<P>
The air ban is the latest in a flurry of efforts to keep
sanctions going against Burundi in face of increasing evidence
that the embargo is being widely breached.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes leaders agreed conditionally at a summit in
Dar es Salaam Thursday to seek a global oil and arms embargo
against the central African nation, to press for the severance of
diplomatic relations worldwide and to move for seizure of all
Burundi government assets abroad.
</P>
<P>
The summit also pledged to continue regional sanctions
implemented in July 1996 after Major Pierre Buyoya seized power
in Burundi in a bloodless military coup.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi failed to attend the
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
