<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Commandos' Bodies to Be Swapped for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The dismembered remains of
dead Israeli marines in last Friday's fighting are to be swapped
for Lebanese detainees incarcerated in Israel, local press said
today.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General Hassan Nasrallah of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, said there is no doubt that the
remains will only be swapped for detainees (not dead guerrillas).
</P>
<P>
"A swap is in our interest because the issue of detainees in
Israeli jails is of the utmost importance to us," he said, quoted
by local press.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, and the Shiite Muslim Amal movement led by Lebanon's
House Speaker Nabih Berri, are the two major anti-Israeli military
groups in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The remains of Israeli commandos, who were killed when being
ambushed by Lebanese guerrillas and soldiers in south Lebanon last
Friday, is being kept by the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Israeli soldiers were killed, four wounded and one
missing but believed to also be killed, in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
"More than one side has contacted us regarding a swap,"
Nasrallah said.
</P>
<P>
However, he denied having been approached by the Americans. The
Israelis have reportedly contacted the U.S. to initiate a swap.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has not tried to contact us and if they do we will not
lift the telephone receiver," he said, adding that he expected the
swap to take place within a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Strengthens Management over Publication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua)-- Lawmakers in Beijing, the
Chinese capital, have introduced new regulations on publications,
including books and compact discs.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Administrative Regulation for Press and Electronic
Publications requires that all publications be submitted to the
local press administration for approval prior to release.
</P>
<P>
Publishers planning to introduce books from outside China must
receive permission from local press authorities, and related
activities will be subject to annual checks.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, effective as of January 1, 1998, empowers
press administrative departments to adopt tough measure to crack
down on illegal publishing activities.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is currently home to 233 publishing houses, or 40
percent of the national total. In addition, the city is home to
264 newspapers, 2,260 magazines and journals, and 15 electronic
publication units.
</P>
<P>
Between 1995-1996, the city uncovered some 1,200 cases of
illegal publishing activities and infringements on intellectual
property right, with related enforcement actions resulting in the
confiscation of more than 1.3 million illegal books and 500,000
compact discs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Helps Reduce Uganda's Debt Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands government
has approved a contribution of about 7.5 million U.S. Dollars to
the multilateral debt fund in the Bank of Uganda (BU), in a bid
to reduce the latter's debt burden.
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily ''the Monitor'' today, the grant
agreement for the contribution was signed here at the end of last
week by Mayanja Nkangi, Ugandan Finance Minister, and by deputy
Governor E. Lule and the Charge d'Affairs of the Netherlands
Saskia De Lang.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral debt fund was established in December 1995 to
pay debt service to the World Bank, the International Monetary
Fund and the African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Since its inception, the Netherlands has donated a total of
39.5 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
