<HEADLINE> S. Africa Vows to Reduce Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- While the world is
celebrating International Literacy Day today, South Africa has
committed itself to promoting education and reducing illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
The Educations Ministry said in a statement at the weekend
that "reducing illiteracy in South Africa has specific
significance because it is integral to the reconstruction and
development of our country".
</P>
<P>
"Literacy is regarded as an important vehicle for social,
political and economic upliftment of all South Africans," the
statement noted.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which abolished apartheid system in 1994, has
been making great efforts to popularize education throughout the
country, especially among the black people, who were poorly
educated in apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
The interim guidelines for adult basic education and training,
one of measures taken by the South African government, is aimed
at the recruitment of 2.5 million learners by the year 2000.
</P>
