<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Issues Loans to Save Lake Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has disbursed
32.5 million Shillings (540,000 U.S. Dollars) to Kenya for the
removal of the water hyacinth from Lake Victoria#,the Daily
Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The money is the first instalment of 1.6 billion Shillings
(26.7 million Dollars) due to Kenya for the conservation of the
lake and is budgeted to facilitate environmental activities for
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has decided to issue a total of 4.9 billion
Shillings (81.7 million Dollars) to all the three east African
countries ashore the lake -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The hyacinth now covers an area of more than 70,000 hectares
of the lake in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
About 60 million neochetina beetles, an acclaimed natural
enemy of the hyacinth, would be released in at least 150 stations
on the Kenyan side this year, making Kenya the first in east
Africa to advocate the use of beetles in hyacinth fighting.
</P>
<P>
The water hyacinth weed, one of the fastest-growing plants in
the earth, was first noticed in Lake Victoria in 1980s, but did
not pose a significant problem until 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
