<HEADLINE> HK Overnight Crackdown Nets 684 Motorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong police caught 684
speeding drivers during a weekend blitz against traffic offenses,
local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three road blocks were set up across the city during the
four-hour operation which ended 2 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Police stopped 566 of the 684 vehicles they saw
speeding. Twenty seat belt offenses were also recorded.
</P>
<P>
The officers issued 522 fixed-penalty tickets and two summonses
for speeding or failing to wear a seat belt. Other drivers who
were not stopped would be sent summonses shortly.
</P>
<P>
Forty-five drivers were given breathalyser tests and five were
arrested for drink-driving.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was promoted by a recent spate of serious road
accidents, said a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, one was killed and 12 injured when a bus careened
over a pavement in Monkok, Kowloon, and into a snack shop.
</P>
<P>
Five days earlier, three died and 10 were injured when a police
car lost control in Central, Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
Five people died and 280 were injured last week alone in road
accidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
