<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Reelected Japan's LDP President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today was reelected unchallengedly for a second term as
the president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
Registration for candidacy opened at LDP headquarters at 11
a.m. and Hashimoto was the only candidate at the presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, 60, is the first LDP president in 13 years to get a
second two-year term since former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasono
in November 1984.
</P>
<P>
His reelection will be formally endorsed at a plenary session
of the LDP members in both houses of the Diet (parliament)
scheduled for Thursday. After that, he is expected to name key
party posts and reshuffle the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
He was first elected LDP president in September 1995 in an
overwhelming victory over his sole rival, Junichiro Koizumi, the
current health and welfare minister.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto took the helm of a coalition government of the LDP,
Social Democratic Party (SDP) and Sakigake in January 1996 from
Tomiichi Murayama, head of the SDP, and launched his second
cabinet in last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
