<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Economy to Grow by 6-7 Percent in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- India's economic prospects
for 1997-98 (april,1997-march 31,1998) are favorable and the
growth rate could be at six to seven percent, said the annual
report of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), which is made public
here today.
</P>
<P>
There is growing recognition that it is possible to achieve and
sustain real gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate of seven
percent or more in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The average real GDP growth rate during the Eighth Five-Year
Plan (1992-97), estimated to be at 6.5 percent, was distinctly
higher than the targeted growth rate of 5.6 percent. More
importantly, the real GDP growth rate during the last three years
averaged over seven percent, which was not only unprecedented for
the economy but also impressive in terms of cross-country
comparisons, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The high growth performance has been achieved along with
notable improvement in several macro-economic fundamentals in the
economy including a lower order of fiscal deficit, a higher saving
rate, a moderation in price increase, sustainable external
payments situation and a relatively stable exchange rate
environment.
</P>
<P>
"The constraints on growth are no longer the availability of
domestic savings or external resources as they used to be earlier.
the limit to overall growth will be set by physical constraints
such as lack of infrastructure facilities and inadequate growth in
agriculture. Besides, it is necessary to ensure a stable financial
environment of which fiscal consolidation must be an integral
part," the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Confident in Canal's Handover in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Panama has the confidence
and ability to run the Panama Canal efficiently and competitively
after its handover by the United States in 1999.
</P>
<P>
President Ernesto Perez Balladares said this today at the
opening ceremony of an International Panama Canal Conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the main purpose of the meeting is to make it known
that the Panamanian government has made all efforts to prepare for
the Canal's handover in 1999. "And now we can say preparations are
well done."
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government has revised some of its Constitution
articles to ensure the independent administrative and financial
management of the canal by the Canal Authority of Panama, said the
president.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which ends Wednesday, will focus on the
technical issues associated with the canal's handover,
maintenance, increasing locks reliability and long-term expansion
plans such as building a third set of locks.
</P>
<P>
The conference was also held in memory of the 20th anniversary
of the signing of the Panama Canal Treaty on September 7,
1977. According to the treaty, the United States will handover the
canal to Panama and withdraw its troops and military presence in
the Panama Canal region before December 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
