<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- President Farooq Leghari
today urged the government to take effective measures to improve
the country's dismal literacy rate, saying otherwise Pakistan
cannot ensure its survival in the increasingly competitive world.
</P>
<P>
"To flourish in the new global markets of the 21st century are
likely only those nations which achieve a very high level of
education, skills and technology," Leghari said in his message on
International Literacy day being observed throughout the world
today.
</P>
<P>
If Pakistan, whose literacy rate is around 30 percent, has to
ensure its survival in this competitive world, he said, it is
imperative that "we invest judiciously in the education sector."
</P>
<P>
"It is rather painful for us to note that our literacy rate is
among the lowest in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The President said education played a central place in the
process of nation building.
</P>
<P>
"It is a means by which nations acquire collective identity and
consciousness which in turn contributes towards national pride,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the whole society to join hands with the government in
the monumental task of tackling literacy.
</P>
<P>
The government is devoting special attention towards education
in its development agenda, he said, but it must be recognized that
this task cannot be effectively handled through government
resources alone.
</P>
<P>
While the government will take the lead, all segments of the
society, particularly non-governmental organizations, must step
forward and participate in this national endeavor, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
