<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Police Cracks Down on Colombo's Underworld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Colombo Detective Bureau
(CDB) was able to put a stop to internecine killings by launching
a massive crackdown on Colombo's underworld, local reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
In the past several weeks, the CDB has arrested 17 key suspects
of local rival gangs, who were competing for the city's narcotics
market, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"We have evidence to prove that those so far arrested are
responsible for 18 of the over 40 drug-related murders committed
since 1995," CDB sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A large quantity of weapons and ammunitions, including
automatic pistols, revolvers and grenades, were recovered from the
possession of the suspects and their hide-outs in the crackdown.
But the CDB admitted that there is still more to be recovered.
</P>
<P>
CDB sources said the arsenal, which these suspects possessed,
pointed to the possibility of their being contracted by terrorists
to carry out acts of destruction and even assassinations in
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The CDB is also investigating the possibility of the city's
underworld having Tamil rebels connections.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the CDB was able to disturb cells of
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) operating in the city
and its suburbs, with the arrests of 17 terrorists, including some
of their key leaders.
</P>
<P>
Drug-traffickers often use boats and planes as means of
transportation to carry heroin into this island nation, from which
they could smuggle the drugs into India. Generally three to five
kilograms of heroin are brought in on a single run.  
</P>
</TEXT>
