<HEADLINE> U.S. Extends GSP to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States has extended
trade facilities to Indonesia under the terms of the generalized
system of preferences (GSP) until June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Antara news agency today quoted a report from the Indonesian
Trade and Industry Ministry as saying that the document signed by
U.S. President Clinton in August.
</P>
<P>
The GSP facility for Indonesia has actually expired on May 31,
1997. However, as the facility still played an important role in
boosting Indonesia's exports to the United States, the Indonesian
government has been consistently lobbying that country, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has in the past come under attack for its labor
policies, which prompted U.S. officials to investigate whether or
not to cut off trade privileges.
</P>
<P>
Antara noted that the U.S. Congress had once petitioned that
the privileges be withdrawn because of the improvement in the
Indonesian economy.  
</P>
