<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Central Bank: Rupiah Won't Fall Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- There should be no further
fall in the Indonesian currency of rupiah as rapid depreciation
over the past few weeks has corrected it, a spokesman of Bank
Indonesia (BI), the central bank, predicted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of Southeast Asian foreign exchange
dealers held in Bali, Indonesia, on Saturday, BI managing director
Paul Soetopo Tjokronegoro said market perception that the rupiah
was slightly overvalued had triggered recent volatility, according
to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Central banks from the Philippines, Indonesia and Singapore met
with foreign exchange dealers in a closed-door conference in Bali,
in a move that was regarded as a way of combating the currency
instability in the region, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"This overvaluation has certainly been corrected now by the
depreciation we have experienced since July," Paul said in his
keynote address.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the rupiah had fallen by some 20 percent in two
months.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah ended on Friday at 2,970 against the U.S. dollar, up
from 3,035 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the head of the Monetary Management Department at
Bank Indonesia, C. Harinowo, who represented the bank at the
meeting, said no conclusions had been reached during the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed what had happened lately and what steps we had
taken to address this," Harinowo said. "There was nothing special
in this meeting."
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian currencies have been under speculative attacks
in the past few weeks, beginning with the Thai baht. The contagion
effect spread over Southeast Asia, first to the Philippine peso,
then moving to the Malaysian ringgit, the Indonesian rupiah and
even the Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
Some economic analysts said that the currency volatility is not
over yet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
