<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Hopes to Launch European Currency Next Spring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Romano Prodi said
today Italy has no intention to propose a postponement for the
launch of the European single currency and would be prepared to
see it launched as early as next spring.
</P>
<P>
His comments made in an interview with the Spanish newspaper
ABC came only a few days after Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
indicated that he would be happy to see the currency launch,
officially scheduled for January 1, 1999, postponed for a year.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Italy was quite ready to be part of the currency
when launched and had no intention of proposing a postponement.
</P>
<P>
"We would even, in theory, be prepared to bring entry forward,"
he said. He indicated that Europe should be united in view of the
world economic trends and the competition coming from Asia.
</P>
<P>
On the question of bringing forward the launch of the Euro, he
noted that time was anyway short, but said it would not be "such
an absurdity, to the extent that Italy would be prepared to do it
even in the spring of next year."
</P>
<P>
The longer the delay, "the greater the chance of speculation
and the more vulnerable our currency will become," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi added, "In a couple of months all the economic data of
all the countries will be clear and therefore it would be possible
to anticipate entry to it."
</P>
<P>
He added that the crucial thing was that the launch should not
be delayed. Asked about current problems for Europe resulting from
the weakness of the German economy, Prodi said he believed that
weakness was only temporary, caused by the cost of unification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
