<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Everything has been going
very well with preparations for the upcoming World Bank and
International Monetary Fund (IMF) annual meetings, said Tim
Cullen, representative of the World Bank in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We've established a fairly good relationship with the Hong
Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), and the arrangements being carried
 out by the HKMA are quite satisfactory," said Cullen in an
exclusive interview with Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The WB and IMF annual meetings and the many related seminars,
to take place in Hong Kong from the middle of this month, will be
 attended by state leaders, finance ministers and central bank
governors from 181 member countries and regions, as well as
officials of international organizations and private bankers.
</P>
<P>
A senior advisor of the World Bank, Cullen was sent to Hong
Kong to coordinate between the World Bank and the HKMA the
preparations for the meetings.
</P>
<P>
"The HKMA is a tremendous partner of the World Bank in this
effort," he said. "I think people from the World Bank who are in
charge of the annual meetings should feel this is really one of
the best experiences they have had in working with a local
authority."
</P>
<P>
He said that for China this is really a good opportunity just
three months after the handover to be able to demonstrate to the
world's financial community that "one country, two systems" is
working very well, and Hong Kong continues to be a very major
financial center in this region.
</P>
<P>
"Having the World Bank and IMF meetings here, along with all
the private bankers who will come as well, is in a way a vote of
confidence in Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that as the venue for the meetings, there has to be a
really large good conference center which can hold a very large
number of people, and Hong Kong's new convention center is
obviously outstanding in this respect. In addition, Hong Kong has
a lot of good hotels which can hold all the attendants coming to
the meetings.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is a modern city right in the heart of East Asia,
while the World Bank has many very important clients in this
region. It's the opportunity for all of the people coming to the
meetings to look at the economic progress being made in East Asia
and to look at the challenges that East Asia still faces in the
years ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about impressions of Hong Kong, Cullen said he found
Hong Kong is a very efficient, friendly and energetic place.
</P>
<P>
"It's interesting of being in Hong Kong at the moment when
there is the currency turmoil in a number of East Asian countries,
 and yet Hong Kong dollar remains very stable," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this demonstrates that Hong Kong is a very solid
financial community in this region. It has a very well managed
financial system, and a huge amount of foreign reserves in hard
currency. Its economic system gives a lot of freedom of activity
for business.
</P>
<P>
Turmoil in East Asian financial markets will certainly be a
topic of discussion at the meetings, he added. The reason is that
people are coming to really discuss whatever issue is important
at the time, in addition to a number of things that are always
important, like the debt of poor countries and the infrastructure
needs in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The meetings will devote a whole day to China-related topics,
and the World Bank has prepared a special report "China 2020",
which will be published on September 18.
</P>
<P>
"China is a country which is in a process of transition to a
market economy, and it's a country which still has a lot of
challenges ahead. Everybody is interested in what is happening in
China," Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank has a very good relationship with
China. At the moment China is the largest borrower from the World
Bank. Over the past years the Chinese government has successfully
managed to improve the life of many poor people, although it has a
 long way ahead to go in completely eliminating poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said through these seminars and meetings, more private
sector money may flow into China to help meet its challenges in
the areas such as poverty-relief, infrastructure and environmental
 issues.
</P>
<P>
The annual meetings, expecting some 2,500 country delegates,
6,000 to 7,000 private bankers, as well as over 2,000 journalists
and many non-governmental organization representatives, will be
the largest ever in WB and IMF history, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
