<HEADLINE> Malaria Spread Warned Among Cambodian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai health officials in Surin
province in northeastern Thailand are warning that malaria may
spread at a temporary Cambodian refugee camp in the province's Kap
Choeng district, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
An increase in the number of malaria patients has been noticed
since July this year, said Jaturong Teerakanok, health chief of
Surin province.
</P>
<P>
The situation is likely to worsen rapidly at this time of the
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
From July 1 to September 4, 106 patients have been admitted to
Kap Choeng hospital due to malaria, Jaturong said.
</P>
<P>
The increasing number of malaria patients were reportedly due
to the rainy season and cross border travels, especially the
influx of Cambodian refugees who escaped the recent fighting in
their country.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities have sent malaria control units to the
camp and began to test all children there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
