<HEADLINE> Xiamen Witnesses Influx of More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The government of Xiamen, one
of China's five Special Economic Zones, approved 286
overseas-funded projects in the first eight months of this year,
up 22.7 percent on last year's period.
</P>
<P>
The projects involved a total contractual volume of 582 million
US dollars, up four percent over the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
A local trade official noted that city has approved a total of
4,148 overseas-funded businesses by the end of August. Some 349
overseas-funded firms have gone into operation this year, bringing
the total number of operational firms to 3,250.
</P>
<P>
The following two aspects characterize this year's use of
overseas investment:
</P>
<P>
-- A growing number of transnational companies have established
businesses in Xiamen, with major companies including Matsushita
and TDK of Japan, and Boeing and General Motors Corp. from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
-- Over 93 percent of operating overseas-funded businesses have
earned profits, with 61 of them increasing the investment and
expanding production scales during the first eight months of the
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
