<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Accelerates Electric Power Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is accelerating its
electric power development to meet the increasing demand in the
country, The New Light of Myanmar said today.
</P>
<P>
Six hydropower stations, a natural gas power plant and some
waste thermal and steam power stations are being built in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 11,500 megawatt-hours (MWH) of electricity per day
-- 4,500 MWH from hydropower stations and 7,000 MWH from natural
stations -- are being generated and transmitted along a
20,606-kilometer main power line.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, The total installed capacity
for electric power by the state-owned Myanmar Electric Power
Enterprise (MEPE) and other organizations was 1,393 megawatts (MW)
in the 1996-97 fiscal year (from April 1996 to March 1997), up
from 1,322 MW in the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The total electricity generation of the two parties went to
4,905 billion KWH in 1996-97, 328 million KWH more than the
previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show Myanmar's power sector achieved a
growth rate of 7.9 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year over the
previous year's.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
