<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Sets Special Holiday for Sanitary Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region has set October 26 as a special day for
sanitary workers, an official of the regional government has
announced recently.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is believed to be the sixth among all Chinese
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities that have
designated a special day off for sanitary workers.
</P>
<P>
On the same day in 1959, a famous sanitary worker in the
Chinese capital, Shi Chuanxiang was honored for his efforts by a
state leader.
</P>
<P>
A local official said there are 13,000 sanitary workers in
Guangxi. Thanks to their excellent work records, eight of the
region's 13 cities received recognition in the national sanitary
inspection in the past years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Ethylene Project in Trial Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A chemical project, which
will produce 150,000 tons of ethylene annually, has been put in
trial operations in the capital of south China's Guangdong
province.
</P>
<P>
Five major sets of equipment for producing ethylene and other
chemical products were introduced from the United States, Japan,
and Italy. The project has also introduced advanced DCS operations
and control system.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to have an annual sales volume
of over three billion yuan, will help meet the demand for chemical
raw materials in the Zhujiang Delta, and will at the same time
lead to the creation of jobs for some 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The key Eighth Five-Year Plan (1990-1995) construction project
was constructed at a cost of nearly eight billion yuan, a large
portion of which was provided by the China Petrochemical
Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970908.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province to Speed Up Port Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian province
will invest three billion yuan in building 17 more than 10,000-ton
berthes at Fuzhou and Xiamen ports in the next three years, to
facilitate its expanding economic ties with the outside world,
said a senior local official.
</P>
<P>
This is the first phase of the province's plan to build a
transportation system with the Fuzhou and Xiamen ports as the
communication hub before 2010, according to Tang Hanqing, a senior
offical of the provincial transportation bureau.
</P>
<P>
The coastal province will also spend seven billion yuan in
building another 30 berthes of the same size by 2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Fuzhou and Xiamen ports edged among
the top ten in China after building 23 deepwater berthes in the
past five years, with the combined handling capacity soaring to 30
million tons.
</P>
<P>
To secure funds for the ambitious construction program, he
said, the province will issue bonds and stocks. A company
overseeing the construction process will also be established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
