<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT, September 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RABAT -- Former Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko died late
Sunday in the Moroccan capital of Rabat, the official Moroccan
news agency MAP reported.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu, 66, died in the Mohammed V military hospital here at
9:30 p.m. (2130 GMT), the agency said. He was suffering from
prostate cancer. (Morocco-Mobutu-Death)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The debate among German politicians on the introduction
of the planned single European currency, the Euro, heated up again
on Sunday when a German state premier made a concrete call for a
five-year delay for its launch.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Bild on Sunday, Kurt
Biedenkopf, premier of the German state of Saxony, indicated that
he doubted that the European Union (EU) would be ready for the
introduction of the Euro on the planned startup date of January 1,
1999. (Germany-Euro)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Luxembourg Foreign Minister and acting President of
the Council of the European Union, Jacques F. Poos, Sunday
expressed his support for U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's decision to tour the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that your initiative will contribute greatly to
reactivating the search for peace in the region" at this critical
moment of the peace process, Poos said in a letter addressed to
Mrs Albright. Albright is scheduled to go to the Middle East this
week on her first visit to the region since becoming secretary of
state. (EU-Albright-Mideast)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An Israeli F-16 fighter plane crashed Sunday in
the Negev desert during an instruction flight, injuring two
pilots.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted military investigators as saying that the
cause of the crash was that the plane might have collided with a
flying bird. The pilot, an instructor, was seriously injured in
the crash, and his student moderately wounded. They were taken to
a hospital in the southern city of Beersheva for
treatment. (Israel-Plane-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Sunday expressed
the hope that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's visit
to the region would help reactivate the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Seating the Palestinians and Israelis on the negotiating table
is the required action," he told the press at the airport after
the departure of King Hussein of Jordan and Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat who joined President Hosni
Mubarak for a tripartite summit here Sunday. (Egypt-Tripartite
Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi Sunday
issued a positive signal to the European countries, saying that
EU ambassadors are welcome back to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted the foreign minister as
saying that "EU ambassadors could return to Tehran any time at
their pleasure." (Iran-EU-Ties) 
