<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Media Active on Voicing People's Wishes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guangming Daily, a leading newspaper that targets
intellectuals, publishes the column "Monthly Focus," which deals
with a key issue that has gained prominence over the past month.
</P>
<P>
One report told about a senior agronomist in Shaanxi Province
who spent 20 years improving the productivity and quality of a
strain of black rice. The improved variety brought riches to many,
but the research institute where the man worked was on the verge
of bankruptcy, and the agronomist had a tough time providing for
his family.
</P>
<P>
The story is representative of the type of trouble faced by
many agricultural experts, and dozens of newspapers and magazines
re-printed the column. As a result, agricultural experts across
the country wrote letters to the Guangming Daily soliciting help
for the man. And after reading the report, Shaanxi's top
government and Party officials immediately instructed provincial
and local authorities to appropriate 100,000 yuan for the research
institute.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of such coverage has led to a breakthrough for
the Chinese media, which has been facilitated by the country's
reform and opening-up, said Xu Renzhong, chief of Xinhua's
Journalism Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
"News reports not only should be channels for informing the
public of the achievements in different fields, but also as a
means of relaying common people's wishes," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
He said the purpose of probing reports not only is to simply
uncover them, but also to raise the public's awareness and that of
the government departments in charge, so that solutions can be
found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
