<HEADLINE> Chinese Media Active on Voicing People's Wishes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- It's the prime-time viewing
hour on Chinese TV, and flashing across screens nationwide is a
purchasing agent for a Shanghai textile mill desperately trying to
explain why he sold 20,000 yuan-worth of contaminated cotton to an
unsuspecting buyer.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the distraught man admits on-camera that he accepted a
bribe to commit the fraud.
</P>
<P>
It's a typical scene from "Focus Report," one of many popular
programs emerging from a new media trend in the country, which uses
investigative journalism to examine problems plaguing modern-day
Chinese society.
</P>
<P>
Since it was first aired on April 1, 1994, by China Central
Television (CCTV), the show has led CCTV'S ratings for all regular
programming due to its bold coverage of issues and follow-ups on
the stories.
</P>
<P>
In the print media, Outlook, China's leading weekly
news-magazine, carried in its first issue in 1994 a column called
"Eye on Important Issues" -- a close cousin of CCTV's Focus Report.
</P>
<P>
One column uncovered a case in a central China city involving
the all-too-common tendency of some officials to falsify
statistics about work reports and performance.
</P>
<P>
The article pointed out that such corruption must be
checked. Well received by readers, the report had widespread
social repercussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
