<HEADLINE> European Paper Industry Lackluster in 1996: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The European paper industry
logged a weak performance in 1996, according to the Confederation
of European Paper Industries (CEPI), in its recently published
annual report.
</P>
<P>
A slower rate of production in 1995 continued into the first
quarter of 1996. The trend was reversed when activity perked up in
the second half of the year, but the performance for the whole of
1996 was far from outstanding, says the report.
</P>
<P>
Paper and board production in 1996 declined slightly by 0.7
percent to 72.8 million tons in Europe, half a million tons
below the 1995 level but still higher than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Total exports increased slightly by 0.7 percent to 41.1 million
tons and imports increased by 0.5 percent to 34 million,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
After two years of firm increases -- 5.1 percent in 1994 and
4.2 percent in 1995, newsprint production fell strongly by 4.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The CEPI says it does not expect any major change in 1997,
adding that the recovery experienced during the first half of 1997
is unlikely to continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
