<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Textiles Industry Sees Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Production of textiles in the
European Union (EU) rose by 1.7 percent during the first quarter
of 1997, after a decline spanning seven consecutive quarters,
according to the most recent quarterly bulletin of the European
Observatory of Textiles and Clothing.
</P>
<P>
Most of the EU member states, in particular Finland, Greece and
Belgium, recorded higher textiles production, though output in
Denmark plunged.
</P>
<P>
However, the decline in clothing production continued during
the first quarter of 1997. Belgium suffered the sharpest drop at
21.4 percent while Sweden's industry grew by 19.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The EU's imports of textile products continued to expand during
the last quarter of 1996. During 1996 as a whole, exports of
textiles increased by 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports to other EU nations and third countries rose in nearly
half the member states during 1996 and fell in the other half. The
largest positive change was seen in Greece while Belgium and
Ireland recorded large decreases.
</P>
<P>
Exports of clothing to third countries grew strongly during the
last quarter of 1996 and by 11.2 percent for the year as a whole,
says the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
