<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Environment Minister Robert Hill, the most senior republican
in Prime Minister John Howard's government, Sunday urged prominent
Australians with open minds on the question to seek election to
next year's constitutional convention. Pro-republicans aim to
reach a consensus at the convention on the question whether
Australia should become a republic.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The federal cabinet will try to find a middle-ground
position on cuts to textile, clothing and footwear tariffs
tomorrow after business groups and the National Party's senior
figures took opposing positions Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's recent changes to its tax law are threatening to
freeze out Australian firms from 146 billion US dollars worth of
major privatization over the next 10 years. The changes mean the
foreign companies, particularly from the U.S. and Asia, are in a
better book and cash flow position to make competitive bids for
Australian infrastructure projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
