<HEADLINE> German Politician Calls for 5-Year Delay on Euro Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The debate among German
politicians on the introduction of the planned single European
currency, the Euro, heated up again on Sunday when a German state
premier made a concrete call for a five-year delay for its launch.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Bild on Sunday, Kurt
Biedenkopf, premier of the German state of Saxony, indicated that
he doubted that the European Union (EU) would be ready for the
introduction of the Euro on the planned startup date of January 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the EU should delay the Euro for five years
to enable its member states to meet all the preconditions for a
common currency. During the interim period, the 16 EU states
should first introduce fixed exchange rates between their
different currencies, he added.
</P>
<P>
Biedenkopf, a senior member of German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
ruling Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party, made the call just
days after leaders of the CDU and its sister party Christian
Social Union (CSU) agreed during a summit meeting to put an end to
the Euro debate in Germany and pledged to hold on to its punctual
start.
</P>
<P>
Germany has stirred up controversies in European capitals last
week when Hans Tietmeyer, president of Germany's central bank,
said in a newspaper interview that a delay of the Euro would not
be "a disaster".
</P>
<P>
In order to quell speculations that Bonn is now in favor of
delaying the Euro, both Chancellor Kohl and Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel made statements later saying that Germany would still stick
to the Euro timetable with strict adherence to the qualification
criteria.
</P>
<P>
Despite the assurances, the Euro debate apparently continues in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Biedenkopf, Edmund Stoiber, premier of the German
state of Bavaria and a well-known Euro sceptic, on Sunday also
repeat his call for a Euro delay.
</P>
<P>
"The Euro should not be allowed to be created at any price," he
was quoted by German media as saying.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German business daily Handelsblatt,
Hans-Peter Stihl, leader of the German umbrella organization of
chambers of commerce DIHT, also said he agreed that a delay of the
Euro would not be an economic disaster so long as another
timetable was agreed upon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
